@NODE Distribution Distribution
@TOC MAIN

    AmiCAD has been written by R.Florac. The AmiCAD package is
    Copyright © 1998-2006 R.Florac, it's not public domain.

    AmiCAD is distributed under the concept of giftware/emailware.
    It can be used only for personal usage, professional usage is strictly
    forbidden without my permission, contact me for that.

    It is allowed to put this program only
      · into AmiNet
      · on AmiNetCDs

    You can @{"reach me" LINK Auteur} by sending your E-mails on the net.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Requirements "Requirements"
@TOC MAIN

    AmiCAD is a program written in C (GCC Compiler 4.0.2, for version 2.19).

    AmiCAD requires the following:
      - Amiga OS4 system
      - PowerPC

    It's an electronics vector sheets editor. It uses only integers for
    faster and simpler working. Its ARexx interface gives it more than 180
    commands, user defined functions are also available. It can use it's own
    variables (integer maths and strings).

    The program can work with many documents at the same time, as long as memory
    is available. Each document is handled by a separate task, allowing multiple
    operations at the same time (Ex. printing a document while doing a
    simulation in a second document). Each document can now have several pages.

    Advanced functions of the system are used: @{"AppIcon" LINK AppIcon}, @{"Pools" LINK Pools}...

    Since version 2.12, you can create documents including several pages,
    each page being edited in a separate window.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Installation Installation
@TOC MAIN

    The simplest method of installation is to use the provided Installer
    script.  The Installer program is required for this to work.
    The preference files AmiCAD.prefs and AmiCAD.keys must be copied into the
    same drawer as the AmiCAD program.
    The AmiCAD.guide @{"help" LINK "Aide en ligne"} file can be copied anywhere
    you like, you only have to set the AmiCAD tooltype @{"HELPFILE" LINK HELPFILE} to the
    corresponding path (HELP: for example).
@ENDNODE
@NODE Running "Running the program / ToolTypes"
@TOC MAIN

    The stack used by AmiCAD can be set to 8 kB only.

    AmiCAD can be started from the CLI or the Workbench (by double
    clicking on it's icon).

    @{b}Running from a CLI (or Shell)@{ub}
    The template of the command is:

  AmiCAD FILE/M,PUBSCREEN/K,HELPFILE/K,LIBS/K,CLIPS/K,STARTUP/K,MASKS/K,MODELS/K

    AmigaDOS wildcards can be used:

  AmiCAD #?.sheet   ==> all files with the extension ".sheet"
			will be loaded into individual windows.

    You can start the program without giving it a file name: the title
    "NoName" will be used by default.

    The keyword HELPFILE gives the path where the help file can be found:

  Example:
      AmiCAD HELPFILE HELP:AmiCAD.guide

    The keyword LIBS gives the path where the symbol libraries are stored:

  Example:
      AmiCAD LIBS Work:AmiCAD/Symbols

    The keyword CLIPS gives the path where the clips are stored:

  Example:
      AmiCAD CLIPS Work:AmiCAD/Clips

    The keyword STARTUP gives the program the name of an ARexx script
    that will be run at startup.

  Example:
      AmiCAD STARTUP startup.AmiCAD

    All these keywords can be associated in a single command:

  AmiCAD HELPFILE HELP:AmiCAD.guide LIBS Work:AmiCAD/Symbols NewSheet

    @{b}Running from Workbench@{ub}
    You only have to click twice on the icon of the program or on an icon
    associated to a file saved with AmiCAD.

      The program icon accepts the seven tooltypes described here:
    @{"  HELPFILE  " LINK HELPFILE},
    @{"  PUBSCREEN " LINK PUBSCREEN}
    @{"   STARTUP  " LINK STARTUP},
    @{"    LIBS    " LINK LIBS},
    @{"   CLIPS    " LINK CLIPS},
    @{"   MASKS    " LINK MASKS}
    @{"   MODELS   " LINK MODELS}
    @{"   X_ICON   " LINK X_ICON},
    @{"   Y_ICON   " LINK Y_ICON},

      Use the Workbench Information menuitem to display and modify them.

    When the program is running, all the requesters that are open can be
    closed by clicking on the gadgets or with the keyboard, (sometimes with
    the right mouse button also). ESC can replace a click on CANCEL, ENTER
    can replace YES or OK.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Objets "The different AmiCAD objects"

     AmiCAD objects are :

	@{"Lines          " LINK Wire}
	@{"Junctions      " LINK Connection}
	@{"Components     " LINK Component}
	@{"References     " LINK Reference}
	@{"Values/Types   " LINK Value}
	@{"Labels         " LINK Label}
	@{"Connectors     " LINK Connector}
	@{"Texts          " LINK Text}
	@{"Boxes          " LINK Rectangle}
	@{"Ellipses       " LINK Ellipses}
	@{"Triangles      " LINK Triangles}
	@{"Arcs           " LINK Arcs}
	@{"Groups         " LINK Groupes}

    Each of these objects can be placed using the mouse (an the Drawing
    menu) They also can be placed using an ARexx script or a macro command.

    They can be edited using a requester, that can be opened by
    a double click with the left mouse button on the object.
    These requesters can apply the changes to the lonely object
    being edited or to several objects using the Application
    gadget in combination with the Extend buttons.

    You can also edit several objects using a button toolbar or a
    key associated to the @{"EDITMUL" LINK EDITMUL} function.

    You can move some objects by clicking on them using the left mouse
    button, and dragging it with the mouse button pushed.
    You can also select several object using a SHIFT key or the
    @{"Edition/Multiselection" LINK Multiselection} menu.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Dashed "Dashed Lines"
@TOC Wire

    These lines can be used to draw some lines, boxes, triangles
    and even components.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Double "Double lines"
@TOC Wire

    These lines can be used to draw some power elements.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Bus "Bus"
@TOC Wire

    Bus can be used to draw some sheets where adresses or
    data buses ar used.
    Each wire connected to the bus must have a label.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Special "Special lines"
@TOC Wire

    These lines can be used to draw some parts of the sheet that
    are non electrical parts. You can use them to draw lines,
    boxes, arcs and triangles.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Wire "Lines"
@TOC Objets

    AmiCAD lines can have several types :
	- wires
	- @{"doubles" LINK Double} lines
	- @{"bus" LINK Bus}
	- @{"special lines" LINK Special}
	- @{"Dashed lines" LINK Dashed}
    The script creating the netlists use only wires to make Spice
    simulations or AmiPCB boards.

    You can use the @{"Drawing/Place wire" LINK "Place wire"} to @{"Drawing/Any width" LINK "Any width"}
    or @{"DRAW" LINK DRAW} and @{"DRAWMODE" LINK DRAWMODE} commands to draw lines.

    Each line can be linked to a @{"label" LINK Label}.

    To edit a line you can click on an extremity and drag this
    point using the mouse with the left button pushed.
    You can also make a double click, opening the edition
    requester. You can then modify :
	- the coordinates
	- the line type
	- the pen width (0 is for dashed lines)
	- the associated label
@ENDNODE
@NODE Connection "The junctions"
@TOC Objets

    Junctions allow to join several wires.
    They can be drawn using a circle or a box (alternate form).
    Warning : some scripts creating the netlists dont use the
    alternate version.

    Pour les placer, vous pouvez utiliser le menu @{"Dessin/Placer connexion" LINK "Place junction"}
    ou la macro @{"JUNCTION" LINK JUNCTION}.

    You can modify the junctions by a double click, opening
    the Reaction edition requester, you can change :
	- the placement
	- horizontal size (or vertical)
	- the symbol, normal 'ellipse, circle) or alternate (box).
@ENDNODE
@NODE Component Components
@TOC Objets

    Components are compound objects, included in library files.
    Each library include some different symbols.

    Libraries are normaly placed in the "Bibliothčques" drawer of AmiCAD. But
    this path can be modified using the @{"LIBS" LINK LIBS} tooltype, or @{"running" LINK Lancement} the
    program or with the Arexx @{"LIBSPATH" LINK LIBSPATH} command.

    All components included in the libraries are defined using a
    10x10 grid. Connections are always on this grid.
    A double click on a component open the edition requester.
    The placement, the scales (horizontal and/or vertical), the
    width of the pen, a horizontal reflection, rotations, and
    alternate symbol (if available), the gate (if they are several),
    and numbering the pins can be defined.

    A @{"reference" LINK Reference} and a @{"value" LINK Value} can also be defined using
    this requester. These two objects can then be moved.

    A AmiPCB mask can be associated to a component (usefull to
    export netlists to AmiPCB). The @{"MASKS" LINK MASKS} tooltype have to
    be defined to make AmiCAD find AmiPCB masks.

    A Spice simulation model can also be associated to a component
    to make Spice able to perform a simulation of a circuit.
    The @{"MODELS" LINK MODELS} tooltype must be defined to find the
    Spice simulation models.

    The libraries can't be edited for the moment. Use some @{"clips" LINK clip}
    if you want to draw a specific component (group all objects).
@ENDNODE
@NODE Reference "References associated to components"
@TOC Objets

    Each @{"component" LINK Component} can have two attributes: a reference and
    a value (or a type, for an integrated circuit for example).

    The reference can be placed when placing the component or
    placed as a text and linked to the component later, using
    the @{"LINKREF" LINK LINKREF} function.

    Editing can be done by a double clik on the reference itself
    or on the component.
    This object have the same properties than @{"texts" LINK Text}.

    A reference can be changed in a normal text by unlinking it.
    You have to use the @{"UNLINK" LINK UNLINK} function to perform it :
	UNLINK(FIRSTSEL)    unlink the first selected object
    You can program a key sequence, a button toolbar or a menu to
    this command.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Value "Values and types associated to components"
@TOC Objets

    Each @{"component" LINK Component} can have two attributes: a reference and
    a value (or a type, for an integrated circuit for example).

    The value (or the type) can be placed when placing the component or
    placed as a text and linked to the component later, using
    the @{"LINKVAL" LINK LINKVAL} function.

    Editing can be done by a double clik on the value itself
    or on the component.
    This object have the same properties than @{"texts" LINK Text}.

    A value can be changed in a normal text by unlinking it.
    You have to use the @{"UNLINK" LINK UNLINK} function to perform it :
	UNLINK(FIRSTSEL)    unlink the first selected object
    You can program a key sequence, a button toolbar or a menu to
    this command.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Label "The labels"
@TOC Objets

    Labels are used with wires, to be able to create netlists.
    They are texts but with a special link.

    To place a label, you can use on the two nextmethods :
    - place a wire, edit this wire and define the label
    - place a wire and a text, then select the two objects
    and a command like this :
	LINKLAB(FIRSTSEL,NEXTSEL(FIRSTSEL))

    Then they can modified editing the wire or the label itself.

    When you click on a wire linked to a label, the two objects are
    selected. But if you click on the label the wire will not be
    selected, so you can move the label where you want (don't
    place it too far...)

    A label can be changed in a normal text by unlinking it.
    You have to use the @{"UNLINK" LINK UNLINK} function to perform it :
	UNLINK(FIRSTSEL)    unlink the first selected object
    You can program a key sequence, a button toolbar or a menu to
    this command.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Connector "The connectors"
@TOC Objets

    The connectors are used to define inputs or outputts on the
    sheet. There exists elsewhere two types of connectors (input or
    output). They have a anchor point placed on one of their sides
    (on the right for an input, on the left for an output, when they
    do not have been reflected). The direction of the arrow can be
    changed into their making undergo a symmetry (after a double click,
    in the edition requester). If you select a connector, then
    use the Drawing/Reflection menu, the selected connector will
    change its type (input to output, output to input).

    Use the @{"Drawing/Place input connector" LINK "Place input connector"} menu, the
    @{"Drawing/Place output connector" LINK "Place output connector"} or one of
    the functions @{"INPUT" LINK INPUT} or @{"OUTPUT" LINK OUTPUT} to place these objects.

    It's possible to modify them by doing a double click with the
    left mouse button, opening the Reaction edition requester.
    You can change these properties :
	- placement
	- vertical and horizontal scales
	- pen width
	- horizontal reflection (arrow pointing)
	- orientation (rotations)
	- the string
@ENDNODE
@NODE Text "Texts"
@TOC Objets

    Texts are used to annotate the sheets. They can be linked
    to components to create their references and value, or to
    lines to define their labels. Use functions @{"LINKVAL" LINK LINKVAL},
    @{"LINREF" LINK LINKREF} or @{"LINKLAB" LINK LINKLAB} to make
    a link between an existing text and a component (or a line).

    They can be placed using the @{"Drawing/Place text" LINK "Place text"} or the
    @{"WRITE" LINK WRITE} function.

    It's possible to modify them by doing a double click with the
    left mouse button, opening the Reaction edition requester.
    You can change these properties :
	- placement
	- vertical and horizontal scales
	- pen width
	- horizontal reflection
	- orientation (rotations)
	- the string
@ENDNODE
@NODE Rectangle "The boxes (rectangles)"
@TOC Objets

    The boxes make it possible to trace various decorations or
    many particular components. They can be empty (contour
    only is then traced) or filled.

    Their layout is done with the menu @ {"Drawing/Place rectangle" LINK "Place box"}
    or with the @ {"BOX" LINK BOX} function.

    To modify them, you can drag a corner using the left mouse button
    (the operation can be cancelled using the right button).
    If you use the CTRL key you'll draw a square box.

    It's possible to modify them by doing a double click with the
    left mouse button, opening the Reaction edition requester.
    You can change these properties :
	- coordinates of the corners
	- pen width
	- the surface (empty or filled area)
@ENDNODE
@NODE Ellipses "The ellipses"
@TOC Objets

    Ellipses make it possible to trace various decorations or
    many particular components. They can be empty (contour
    only is then traced) or filled.

    They are drawn using the @{"Drawing/Place ellipse" LINK "Place ellipse"} menu
    or the @{"ELLIPSE" LINK ELLIPSE} function.

    The width of the pen used to draw an empty ellipse can be
    any value larger than zero.

    To modify them, you can click on an orthogonal radius extremity,
    then drag it to maximize or minimize the selected radius.
    Using the CTRL key makes it possible to draw a circle.

    It's possible to modify them by doing a double click with the
    left mouse button, opening the Reaction edition requester.
    You can change these properties :
	- placement
	- horizontal and vertical radius
	- pen width (empty ellipse)
	- the surface (empty or filled area)
@ENDNODE
@NODE Triangles "The triangles"
@TOC Objets

    Triangles make it possible to trace various decorations or
    many particular components. They can be empty (contour
    only is then traced) or filled.

    They are drawn using the @{"Drawing/Place triangle" LINK "Place triangle"} menu
    or the @{"TRIANGLE" LINK TRIANGLE} function.

    To modify them, you can click on a corner, and then drag it.
    It's possible to modify them by doing a double click with the
    left mouse button, opening the Reaction edition requester.
    You can change these properties :
	- corners coordinates
	- pen width (empty triangles)
	- the surface (empty or filled area)
@ENDNODE
@NODE Arcs "The arcs"
@TOC Objets

    Arcs make it possible to trace various decorations or
    many particular components.
    They can be drawn using the @{"Drawing/Place arc" LINK Place arc} menu.

    Horizontal and vertical radius can have different sizes.

    It's possible to modify them by doing a double click with the
    left mouse button, opening the Reaction edition requester.
    You can change these properties :
	- placement
	- beginning and ending angles (with a precision of 1 degree)
	- pen width (greater than zero, less than 10).
    The @{"PENWIDTH" LINK PENWIDTH} function can be used to create a width greater
    than 10.

    The @{"ARC" LINK ARC} function can be used to place an arc.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Groupes "The groups"
@TOC Objets

    Groups are created with some objects (lines, junctions, texts,
    labels, etc) being placed and then selected and grouped using the
    @{"Edition/New group" LINK New group} menu.
    You can use them to create some special components, but it's not
    possible to use these groups to perform a simulation or create a
    netlist.

    Groups can be saved in a file, using @{"clips" LINK Clip}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "EditGroup" "Edition of several objects"
@TOC MAIN

    This requester is opened using the @{"EDITMUL" LINK EDITMUL} function, associated
    to a toolbar button or a key.

    The requester can be opened to edit all the objects present on the
    sheet or only several selected objects, or even a group.

    @{b}Filter@{ub}
    The higher button, at the center (Filter), allows to select some
    kind of objects : if you select Lines, only the lines will be
    displayed in the listview, with their properties.
    If you select the first option again, you'll display all the objects
    that were present when opening the requester (a group or the selection).

    @{b}EditinG un object@{ub}
    To modify a given object, do a double clic on its line in the listview
    and the normal Reaction edition requester will be opened to perform
    the edition. Note that the color of a selected object is changed.
    If the requester is validated the data in the listview is updated.
    You can cancel the changes by clicking on the Cancel button, to the
    right bottom of the requester or closing the requester.

    @{b}Direct editing in the listview@{ub}
    Some data can be modified clicking in the listview (click a first time
    to select the object, then wait a short moment to click a second time),
    then the data can be edited directly in the listview. You can use the
    TAB key to edit the next value (in the next column) or Shift-TAB to
    edit the previous value.

    @{b}Simultaneous Edition@{ub}
    You can select several entries in the listview (using the SHIFT key
    or dragging the mouse pointer on the listview). When it's done,
    click on a column header to open a little requester that will ask
    you to enter the value that will be used to fill the field for
    all the selected objects. The value of the last selected entry is
    used to initialize the requester. Note that some columns can't be
    edited (object types, object number, group...).

    @{b}Sorting the data@{ub}
    When there is @{b}no selected entry@{ub} in the listview, you can sort all
    the objects present in the listview, just by clicking on a column
    header.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Barre de titre" "Title bar format"
    There are some indicators on the titlebars of the windows:
    - The name of the file associated to the document (with the @{"complete" LINK "Full name"}
      path or not),
    - a space, the page title,
    - some letters between two braces []:,
      - a + sign if the document has been modified
      - the letter G if @{"snap on grid" LINK "Snap on grid"} is valid,
      - the letter R if components are placed with their @{"Reference" LINK "Place reference"},
      - the letter V if components are placed with their @{"Value" LINK "Place value"},
      - the letter N if components are placed with their @{"pins numbers" LINK "Place pins numbers"},
      - the letter L if lines are @{"pulled" LINK "Pull lines"} while moving components,
      - a number that gives the width of the actual lines that are drawn (0 for
      dashed lines).
      - the cursor coordinates X=...,Y=...
      - the scale factor used to display the objects Z=...% (100% is
      used for normal scale).

    The windows have two proportional gadgets to scroll big sheets larger
    than the screen. The mouse wheel can be used to scroll the content of
    the window in the vertical direction.
    The windows can be @{"iconified" LINK Iconify}, then they have no more gadgets,
    but they take only a little space on the screen.
    Select this window and click on the right button of the mouse or
    press a key to open it again.
@ENDNODE
@NODE HELPFILE "The HELPFILE tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype gives to the program the path to find the guide file.
    This word must be followed by the sign "=" and the path and name
    of the guide file. So you can place it where you want and even
    rename it.

  Example:
      HELPFILE=HELP:AmiCAD.guide
@ENDNODE
@NODE "OUTIL WINDOW" "The WINDOW tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype has been removed in version 2.05.
    Document dimensions are now saved in the file AmiCAD.prefs.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PUBSCREEN "The PUBSCREEN tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype is used to define the screen where AmiCAD will open
    its windows. By default AmiCAD uses its own screen, but you can use
    any public screen, including the Workbench.
@ENDNODE
@NODE STARTUP "The STARTUP tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype gives to the program the name of an @{"ARexx script" LINK Script}
    that will be run at startup. So you can @{"define" LINK DEF} the usual functions you often use,
    if you want.

  Examples:
      STARTUP=startup.amiCAD
      STARTUP=startup
@ENDNODE
@NODE LIBS "The LIBS tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype gives the path where the symbols files are found.
    The default path is the Libs sub-directory, in the AmiCAD directory.

  Examples:
      LIBS=Work:AmiCAD/Symbols
      LIBS=Symbols

  See also: @{"LIBSPATH" LINK LIBSPATH}
@ENDNODE
@NODE CLIPS "The CLIPS tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype gives the path where the clips are found.
    The default path is the Clips sub-directory, in the AmiCAD directory.

  Examples:
      CLIPS=Work:AmiCAD/Clips
      CLIPS=User_symbols

  See also: @{"CLIPPATH" LINK CLIPPATH}
@ENDNODE
@NODE MASKS "The MASKS tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype gives the path where the clips used by AmiPCB
    are found, to set a link between AmiCAD and AmiPCB.
    By default this path is set to /AmiPCB/Clips, so if the two
    programs directories are installed in the same place, all will
    be working.

    @{i}Examples :@{ui}
	MASKS=Work:AmiPCB/Clips
	MASKS=Travail:Projets/AmiPCB/Clips

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"MASKPATH" LINK MASKPATH}
@ENDNODE
@NODE MODELS "The MODELS tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype is used to locate the Spice path for models used
    in simulation. The default path is /Spice/Models, it's necessary
    for it to work that Spice and AmiCAD drawers are installed at
    the same place.

    @{i}Exemples :@{ui}
	MODELS=Work:Spice/Models
	MODELS=Travail:Projets/Spice/Models

    @{i}Voir aussi :@{ui} @{"MODSPATH" LINK MODSPATH}
@ENDNODE
@NODE _MACROS "The MACRO tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype has been removed in version 2.05 of the program.
@ENDNODE
@NODE X_ICON "The X_ICON tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype is used to locate the AmiCAD AppIcon on the
    Workbench screen.

  Example:
      X_ICON=10   puts the icon at the left of the screen.

  See also: @{"Y_ICON" LINK Y_ICON}
@ENDNODE
@NODE Y_ICON "The Y_ICON tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype is used to locate the AmiCAD AppIcon on the
    Workbench screen.

  Example:
      Y_ICON=500  puts the icon at the bottom of the screen.

  See also: @{"X_ICON" LINK X_ICON}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SHEET_WIDTH "The SHEET_WIDTH tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype has been removed in version 2.05.
    Document dimensions are now saved in the file AmiCAD.prefs.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SHEET_HEIGHT "The SHEET_HEIGHT tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype has been removed in version 2.05.
    Document dimensions are now saved in the file AmiCAD.prefs.
@ENDNODE
@NODE GRIDSIZE "The GRIDSIZE tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype has been removed in version 2.05.
    Grid dimensions are now saved in the file AmiCAD.prefs.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Menus "AmiCAD menus"
@TOC Main

    AmiCAD handles 7 menus, they can be used with the right mouse
    button, like any other application on Amiga. Many of them can be
    called using the keyboard, without the right Amiga key.

  @{"Project    " LINK Project}
  @{"Document   " LINK Document}
  @{"Drawing    " LINK Drawing}
  @{"Edit       " LINK Edition}
  @{"Preferences" LINK Preferences}
  @{"Scripts    " LINK Scripts}
  @{"Macros     " LINK Macros}

    Many of these menus can be called using the ARexx function @{"MENU" LINK MENU}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Project "Project menu"
@TOC Menus

    This menu has 11 entries:
    @{"Load file        " LINK "Load document"}     Load a file in the active window.
    @{"Open recent      " LINK "Open recent"}     Select a recent file and open it.
    @{"Save file        " LINK "Save document"}     Save the current document.
    @{"Save as          " LINK "Save as"}     Sve the current document using the asl requester.
    @{"Rename           " LINK Rename}     Rename the current document.
    @{"Filenote         " LINK Filenote}     Annotate a file.
    @{"Kill file        " LINK "Kill file"}     Delete a file.
    @{"Other document   " LINK "Other document"}      Open a new window.
    @{"Sheets           " LINK Sheets}              Displays the document list.
    @{"Help             " LINK Help?}     Displays the AmigaGuide help.
    @{"Quit             " LINK Quit}             Close all the documents.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Load document" "Project menu/Load document"
@TOC Project

    You can choose the document to load with the asl.library requester.
    This library is loaded only when needed. The window takes the name
    of the loaded file.

    If the current window is empty, the document is loaded in it.
    In other cases, a new document is opened.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-O (open) or O

    Note: you can use the @{"AppIcon" LINK AppIcon} present on the Workbench screen for
    loading a file.

  See also: @{"LOAD" LINK LOAD}, @{"OPEN" LINK OPEN}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Load document")     Warning: solid space between
	      (ALT-SPACE) the words load and document.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Open recent" "Project menu/Open recent"
@TOC Project

    This menu is used to select one file choosed between the last 16 files
    that were loaded. A requester is opened with the file names (without the
    path) and you have to click on one of them to open it. If the current
    document is empty the file will be loaded in it, otherwise it will be
    opened in a new window.

    The file list is saved in the AmiCAD.recents file. It can be deleted,
    it will be created and completed when AmiCAD will run again.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Save document" "Project menu/Save document"
@TOC Project

    The document is saved using the current file name in the window.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-S (save) or S

  See also: @{"SAVE" LINK SAVE}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Save document")       Warning: solid space between
	      (ALT-SPACE) the words save and document.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Save as" "Project menu/Save as"
@TOC Project

    The current document is saved using the asl.library requester to
    choose the filename.

    If the file already exists a requester will ask you to confirm
    that you want to overwrite it.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-A (save As) or A

  See also: @{"SAVE" LINK SAVE}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Save as")     Warning: solid space between
	  (ALT-SPACE) the words save and as.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Rename "Project menu/Rename"
@TOC Project

    The asl.library requester is opened and you can choose a filename,
    the current document is renamed using this filename.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-= or =

  See also: @{"FILENAME" LINK FILENAME}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Rename")
@ENDNODE
@NODE Filenote "Project menu/Filenote"
@TOC Project

    The asl.library requester is opened, if you select a file a
    requester asks you for a note to attach to the file.

    This note will be displayed using the AmigaDOS command List or
    with the Workbench menu Icon/Information.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

  ARexx call: MENU("Filenote")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Kill file" "Project menu/Kill file"
@TOC Project

    The asl.library requester is opened, if you select a file, it
    will be deleted.

    Warning: you can't recover the file...

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry (dangerous...).

  ARexx call: MENU("Kill file")   Warning: solid space between
	  (ALT-SPACE) the words kill and file.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Other document" "Project menu/Other document"
@TOC Project

    A new window is opened, the asl.library requester is opened and
    you can select a file to load in it.
    If you want to open a window without loading a file, just use the
    F4 key.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

  See also: @{"NEWSHEET" LINK NEWSHEET}, @{"OPEN" LINK OPEN}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Other document")    Warning: solid space between
	  (ALT-SPACE) the words Other and document
@ENDNODE
@NODE Sheets "Project menu/Sheets"
@TOC Project

    A requester is opened with all the document names. Clicking on one of
    these buttons, makes the corresponding window active.

    Another way to call a window is to do a click on the middle
    @{b}mouse button@{ub}: the requester will be opened.
    Just click on the right button to put it's window in front
    of the screen.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

  See also: @{"REQSHEET" LINK REQSHEET}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Sheets").
@ENDNODE
@NODE Help? "Project menu/Help?"
@TOC Project

    A requester is opened to ask you the name of the node of the AmiCAD.guide
    file you want to be displayed. This file contains many items, there is
    a node for each ARexx macro, with it's name (Ex: COPY, PASTE...)
    You can also have help for each menu entry by selecting the menu entry
    with the right mouse button and pressing the HELP key.
    When there is an error displayed in a requester, if this error is relative
    to an ARexx function, just type the HELP key while the requester is open,
    the AmiCAD.guide will be opened to the corresponding node.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-? or ?

  See also: @{"HELP" LINK HELP}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Help")
@ENDNODE
@NODE Quit "Project menu/Quit"
@TOC Project

    All the documents present in memory are closed. If some of them were
    modified and not saved, a requester will ask you to continue or not.
    The program frees all memory it was using when everything is closed.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-Q or Q (all the windows are closed)

  See also: @{"CLOSE" LINK CLOSE}.

  Arexx call: MENU("Quit")
@ENDNODE
@NODE Document "Document menu"
@TOC Menus

    Documents can include several pages, they have been created in version 2.12 of AmiCAD.
    They are saved in files that have a special header, different of older files, that can
    include only one page, this older format is always used for saving pages.

    @{"New page         " LINK "New page"}     Create a new page in the document
    @{"Load page        " LINK "Load page"}     Load a new page
    @{"Save IFF         " LINK "Save IFF"}     Save the current document in an IFF file.
    @{"Edit             " LINK Edit}     Open a requester to handle pages
    @{"Initialize       " LINK Initialize}     The current window is cleaned.
    @{"Iconify          " LINK Iconify}     Iconify the current window.
    @{"Hide             " LINK Hide}     Close the current window, the document is always in memory.
    @{"Close document   " LINK "Close document"}     Close the document
    @{"Informations     " LINK Informations}        Displays some informations.
    @{"Print            " LINK "Print page"}            Printing of the current page
@ENDNODE
@NODE "New page" "Document menu/New page"
@TOC Document

    This menu entry is used to add a new page to the current document.
    A requester is used to enter the name of the page.
    A document can include 65535 pages... if they can fit in memory !
    The new page takes the dimensions of the current page being edited.
    Pages of a same document are handled by the same task, so you can't
    edit a page, while a script is working on another, unlike for different
    documents.

    Voir aussi : @{"NEWPAGE" LINK NEWPAGE}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Load page" "Document menu/Load page"
@TOC Document

    This menu is used to load a new page (from file) in a document.
    This file must have been created @{"saving a page" LINK "Save page"} or with an old version
    of AmiCAD (before 2.12).
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Save IFF" "Project menu/Save IFF"
@TOC Document

    The current page is saved in a file using the IFF format.
    You can then load this file into a bitmap drawing program
    like Personal Paint, Deluxe Paint or other...
    You can also import the file with a program like ProPage or
    Wordworth.
    The files are saved using only two colours (black lines, white
    background). The grid is not represented.

    The file is selected using the asl.library requester.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

  See also: @{"SAVEIFF" LINK SAVEIFF}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Save IFF")    Warning: solid space between
	  (ALT-SPACE) the words Save and IFF.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Edit "Document menu/Edit"
@TOC Document

    This menu opens a requester allowing some operations on the pages of the document :
	- @{"Select" LINK SelectPage}
	- @{"Save page" LINK "Save page"}
	- @{"Delete" LINK "Delete page"}
	- @{"Rename" LINK Rename}
    The window have a listview including each name of the pages in the document.
    Just select a name and press the button for the command you want to execute
    on it...

    This requester can also be opened clicking twice in an empty place of a page
    with the left button of the mouse.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SelectPage "Pages requester/Select"
@TOC Edit

    The selected page becomes the current page, it can be edited.
    If needed it's placed in front of the screen.

    See also : @{"SETPAGE" LINK SETPAGE}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Save page" "Pages requester/Sauve page"
@TOC Edit

    The selected page is saved in a file (the file is selected using
    an asl.library requester). The format of the file is the page
    format, allowing the page to be loaded in another document using
    the @{"Load page" LINK "Load page"} menu.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Delete page" "Pages requester/Delete"
@TOC Edit

    The selected page is deleted, its content is forever loosed...
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Rename" "Gestion des pages/Renommer"
@TOC Edit

    A requester is opened to choose the name of the selected page.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Initialize "Document menu/Initialize"
@TOC Document

    All the objects of the current page are deleted. If the page was
    modified but not saved, a requester is opened asking you to confirm
    the operation.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

  ARexx call: MENU("Initialize")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Print page" "Document menu/Print page"
@TOC Document

    The page is printed using the printer.device. The current
    system Preferences are used, (printer driver...)

    A requester will ask you for a ratio, if you reply with a value of 1,
    a pixel on screen will be equivalent to a dot on the paper, if you
    reply by 2, the document will be printed twice the size. Try to find
    the best value for your printer density and the dimensions of your
    document.

    WARNING: If the value of the ratio is 0, the operation is aborted.
    Large values consume a lot of CHIP memory.

    If you reply with a good positive value, a second requester will ask
    you if you want to print the document rotated or not, this feature lets
    you print the document horizontally, (no rotation), or vertically.

    The windows are iconified during this process to make more CHIP memory
    available. If you have any problem, try to close some windows or screens
    not in use at the moment.

    A full page button can be pressed to calculate the good ratio to make
    the page fit on the full page.

    For information, the printer driver is displayed, but you have to use
    the Preferences program of the system to change it.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-P (Print) or P

  See also: @{"PRINT" LINK PRINT}

  ARexx call: MENU("Print")
@ENDNODE
@NODE Iconify "Document menu/Iconify"
@TOC Document

    The window is closed, a small window is opened in the top of the screen,
    including only the name of the document (without the path).
    You can select this window and use the right button to reopen it.
    This menu is useful when you work with multiple pages.

    You can place the iconified window whereever you want, when the window
    is iconified again, it will return to this place.

    To close an iconified window without opening it, type CTRL-Q with the
    keyboard when it's selected.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-I (icon) I

  ARexx call: MENU("Iconify")
@ENDNODE
@NODE Hide "Document menu/Hide"
@TOC Document

    The window is closed but the document remains in memory. To reopen
    this window, click on the AppIcon, (on the Workbench screen), if it's
    the only window.
    You can also use the @{"Edit" LINK Edit} menu (Select command) if you are working
    on another page of this document. If you are working on another document, click on
    the middle button of the mouse and select the name of the document you want to
    select.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-$ or $

  ARexx call: MENU("Hide")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Close document" "Document menu/Close document"
@TOC Document

    This menu close all the pages of the current document. If one or
    several pages have been modified you'll be prompted to save them
    or not.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Informations "Document menu/Informations"
@TOC Document

    A requester is opened to display some information :
    copyright, number of objects in the current document, name of the
    ARexx @{"port" LINK Port}, free memory...

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-K or K

  ARexx call: MENU("Informations")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "AppIcon" "AmiCAD AppIcon"
@TOC MAIN

    When AmiCAD is @{"running" LINK Running}, an AppIcon is placed on the
    Workbench screen. It's name is AmiCAD. It's purpose is to load any
    document by dragging it's icon onto this AppIcon. Simple, no?

    This AppIcon has another function: clicking twice on it brings the AmiCAD
    screen to the front. You can use it to recover a window that was closed
    previously (see menu @{"Project/Hide" LINK Hide}).

    If the program seems locked after executing an ARexx script you can
    also try to click on it, if this situation is caused by bad usage
    of the ARexx function @{"LOCK" LINK LOCK}, the problem will be solved.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Pools" "Memory handler"
@TOC MAIN

    Pools are handled by the operating system version 3.0 and later.
    Its purpose is to have a better memory handler, it's faster and
    reduces memory fragmentation.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Drawing" "Drawing menu"
@TOC Menus
    This menu is for drawing objects on the document. All these objects
    are vector oriented. They can be modified with a double click from
    the left mouse button (a requester is opened with gadgets, depending
    on the object type).

    This menu has 28 entries:
    @{"Grid size             " LINK "Grid size"}
    @{"  Snap on grid        " LINK "Snap on grid"}
    @{"Library manager       " LINK "Library manager"}
    @{"Choose component      " LINK "Choose component"}
    @{"Place component       " LINK "Place component"}
    @{"Place reference       " LINK "Place reference"}
    @{"Place value           " LINK "Place value"}
    @{"Place pins numbers    " LINK "Place pins numbers"}
    @{"Rotation              " LINK Rotation}
    @{"Reflection            " LINK Reflection}
    @{"Alternate symbol      " LINK "Alternate symbol"}
    @{"Normal position       " LINK "Normal position"}
    @{"Place line            " LINK "Place wire"}
    @{"Orthogonal mode       " LINK "Orthogonal mode"}
    @{"Continuous drawing    " LINK "Continuous drawing"}
    @{"Double line           " LINK "Double line"}
    @{"Bus                   " LINK Bus}
    @{"Dashed line           " LINK "Dashed line"}
    @{"Any width             " LINK "Any width"}
    @{"Place box             " LINK "Place box"}
    @{"Place triangle        " LINK "Place triangle"}
    @{"Place ellipse         " LINK "Place ellipse"}
    @{"  Filled areas        " LINK "Filled areas"}
    @{"Place arc             " LINK "Place arc"}
    @{"Place junction        " LINK "Place junction"}
    @{"Place text            " LINK "Place text"}
    @{"Place input connector " LINK "Place input connector"}
    @{"Place output connector" LINK "Place output connector"}
    @{"Redraw all            " LINK "Redraw all"}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Grid size" "Drawing menu/Grid size"
@TOC Drawing

    With this menu, you can define the size of the grid that is
    used to space the objects on the document. The default size is 10.
    The components defined in the symbol libraries all use this size.
    But you can choose another size if you want, some users prefer working
    with a size of 5.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-µ or µ

  See also: @{"SETGRID" LINK SETGRID}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Grid size")   Warning: solid space between
     or MENU("Grid")        (ALT-SPACE) the words Grid and size.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Snap on grid" "Drawing menu/Snap on grid"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is marked, the objects are placed on the grid,
    if it's not marked you can place the objects wherever you want,
    but if you place some components like that, you will have some
    difficulties when placing the wires...

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-G or G

  ARexx call: MENU("Snap")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Library manager" "Drawing menu/Library manager"
@TOC Drawing
    A requester is opened with all loaded libraries, the number
    of symbols and the version number of the library is displayed.

    Three buttons allow :
	- to load other libraries (you can't load again an
	already loaded library)
	- to use the current list
	- to flush the selected library (impossible if this
	library is used by a sheet).
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Choose component" "Drawing menu/Choose component"
@TOC Drawing

    A requester is opened to look for a component in the libraries.
    The window has two lists: the left one is for the libraries,
    the right one for the symbols.

    You can load or flush any library using the buttons.
    The other buttons have the same role of the equivalent menus.

    The selected component is displayed in the upper left corner of
    the document window.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-% or %

  See also: @{"PUTPART" LINK PUTPART}, @{"LOADLIB" LINK LOADLIB}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Choose component")    Warning: "solid" space
	    (ALT-SPACE) between the words Choose and component.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Place component" "Drawing menu/Place component"
@TOC Drawing

    This entry enables the component mode. The current symbol is drawn
    under the cursor and you can place it on the document. If no symbol
    is valid, the @{"bgui requester" LINK Choose component} is opened.
    Click with the left mouse button to place a component on the document.
    You are greatly encouraged to use the option @{"Snap on grid" LINK "Snap on grid"} to
    place the components.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-H or H

  See also: @{"PUTPART" LINK PUTPART}

  ARexx call: MENU("Place component")     Warning: solid space
	    (ALT-SPACE) between the words Place and component.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Place reference" "Drawing menu/Place reference"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is marked, when components are @{"placed" LINK Place component} with the
    mouse, it's reference will also be placed next to it.
    This reference can be edited by a double click on the component or
    on the reference itself. You can also move this object at another place
    with the left mouse button (click on it, and drag the mouse while the
    button is held down).
    Default references are defined in the libraries and can't be changed.

    You can call the @{"ARexx script" LINK "Call script"} AddRefs to add the part numbers.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

  See also: @{"SETREF" LINK SETREF}.

  This menu can't be called by ARexx.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Place value" "Drawing menu/Place value"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is marked, when components are @{"placed" LINK Place component} with the
    mouse, it's default value will also be placed next it.
    This value can be edited by a double click on the component or
    on the value itself. You can also move this object at another place
    with the left mouse button (click on it, and drag the mouse while the
    button is held down). The default value is the name of the object.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

    See also: @{"SETVAL" LINK SETVAL}.

    This menu can't be called by ARexx.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Place pins numbers" "Drawing menu/Place pins numbers"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is marked, when components are @{"placed" LINK Place component} with the
    mouse, it's pins will be numbered, if this component is defined with
    pin numbers in the library (always in this case for IC).
    If a component is placed on the document and you want to modify
    this indication, double click on it with the left mouse button and
    click on the button "Pins numbers" to change this option, if it
    can be edited (resistances for example have no pin number).

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"SETPINS" LINK SETPINS}.

    This menu can't be called by ARexx.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Rotation" "Drawing menu/Rotation"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is selected the current symbol or the selected
    objects are rotated by 90 degrees. If you press a SHIFT key while
    selecting the menu the rotation will be anti-clockwise.
    This operation can also be performed on a clip (just select the
    menu Edit/Paste, then this one).

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-R or R (clockwise)
		     AMIGA-SHIFT-R or SHIFT-R (anti-clockwise)

  See also: @{"ROTATE" LINK ROTATE}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Rotation")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Reflection" "Drawing menu/Reflection"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is selected the current symbol or the selected
    objects are mirrored. This operation is done around the vertical
    axis of the objects (or horizontal if they were rotated).
    This operation can also be performed on a clip (just select the
    menu Edit/Paste, then this one).

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-/ or /

  See also: @{"SYMMETRY" LINK SYMMETRY}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Reflection")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Alternate symbol" "Drawing menu/Alternate symbol"
@TOC Drawing

    Select this menu to toggle the symbol definition of a component,
    when it exists in the library. You can perform this operation on
    the current symbol being placed or the selected components.

    This feature is useful for amplifiers for inverting the +
    and - inputs. In some libraries the alternate symbol is an american
    symbol (try the resistance).

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-~ or ~

  See also: @{"CONVERT" LINK CONVERT}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Alternate")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Normal position" "Drawing menu/Normal position"
@TOC Drawing

    This entry invalidates the effects of the precedents @{"rotation" LINK Rotation},
    @{"reflection" LINK Reflection} and @{"Alternate symbol" LINK "Alternate symbol"}.
    You can perform this operation on the current symbol being placed
    or on the selected components.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-N ou N.

  ARexx call: MENU("Normal position")     Warning: solid space between
	  (ALT-SPACE) the words Normal and position.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Place wire" "Drawing menu/Place line"
@TOC Drawing

    This entry enables the wire mode (or line mode). When it's selected
    the cursor is changed (into a cross). To place a line, move the cursor
    to the start and click the left mouse button, now place the cursor
    at the end point and click again with the left button. Click on the
    right button to abort a placement.
    To stop this mode, click on the right button or select another mode.

    The current line width is indicated in the @{"title bar" LINK "Barre de titre"}.
    It can be modified using one of these menus: @{"Double line" LINK "Double line"}, @{"Bus" LINK Bus}, @{"Dashed line" LINK "Dashed line"}
    or @{"Any width" LINK "Any width"}.

    To modify a line, click on an extremity with the left button, and
    holding the button down, drag the mouse to another place.

    You can also use the keyboard to adjust a line: select the line by
    clicking on it, and use the cursor keys with the ALT or CTRL keys to
    modify the beginning or the ending of the line. You can also use the
    SHIFT key to move faster (grid size).

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-SPACE or SPACE

  See also: @{"Orthogonal mode" LINK "Orthogonal mode"}, @{"Continuous drawing" LINK "Continuous drawing"}, @{"Double line" LINK "Double line"},
	@{"Bus" LINK Bus} et @{"Dashed line" LINK "Dashed line"}.
	@{"DRAW" LINK DRAW}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Place wire")      Warning: solid space
	      (ALT-SPACE) between the words Place and line.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Orthogonal mode" "Drawing menu/Orthogonal mode"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is marked, the lines are always placed horizontally
    or vertically, or at an angle of 45 degrees.
    Select this menu to toggle its state.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-| or |

  @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"SETORTHO" LINK SETORTHO}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Orthogonal mode")     Warning: solid space
	    (ALT-SPACE) between the words Orthogonal and mode.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Continuous drawing" "Drawing menu/Continuous drawing"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is marked, when @{"line mode" LINK "Place wire"} is active, a new
    line is placed at the extremity of the precedent.
    Click on the right mouse button to interrupt the continuity of
    the lines.

    Select this menu to toggle its state.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

    This menu can't be called by ARexx.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Double line" "Drawing menu/Double line"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is marked, the lines are drawn with 2 pixels width.

    To stop this mode, select this entry again or choose another mode:
    @{"Bus" LINK Bus}, @{"Dashed line" LINK "Dashed line"} or @{"Any width" LINK "Any width"}.

    Note that the current line width is written in the @{"title bar" LINK "Barre de titre"}.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-\ or \

  See also: @{"DRAWMODE(2)" LINK DRAWMODE}, @{"DRAW" LINK DRAW}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Double line")         Warning: solid space
	    (ALT SPACE) between the words Double and line.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Bus" "Drawing menu/Bus"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is marked, the lines are drawn with 7 pixels width.

    To stop this mode, select this entry again or choose another mode:
    @{"Double line" LINK "Double line"}, @{"Dashed line" LINK "Dashed line"} or @{"Any width" LINK "Any width"}.

    Note that the current line width is written in the @{"title bar" LINK "Barre de titre"}.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-. or .

  See also: @{"DRAWMODE(3)" LINK DRAWMODE}, @{"DRAW" LINK DRAW}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Bus")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Any width" "Drawing menu/Any width"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is marked, the lines can be drawn at any width. A
    requester will ask you for the width you want. Enter a value between 1
    and 255. All the objects that will be placed after this choice,
    will be drawn with this line width.
    If you select this entry while it's marked, the line width becomes 1.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

    See also: @{"DRAWMODE(-X)" LINK DRAWMODE}, @{"DRAW" LINK DRAW}.

    This menu can't be called by ARexx.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Dashed line" "Drawing menu/Dashed line"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is marked, the lines are drawn like dashed lines.
    To cancel this mode, select it again or choose another mode:
    @{"Double line" LINK "Double line"}, @{"Bus" LINK "Bus"} or @{"Any width" LINK "Any width"}.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-: or :

  See also: @{"DRAWMODE(0)" LINK DRAWMODE}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Dashed line")     Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
	      between the words Dashed and line.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Place box" "Drawing menu/Place box"
@TOC Drawing

    When you select this entry, the cursor changes to box mode (like
    in line mode). Click on a corner of the box you want to draw with
    the left button mouse, go to the opposite corner and click again.
    If you want to cancel the operation, click on the right button.

    The boxes are drawn using the current width.

    To modify an existing box, click in a corner, and with the left
    button mouse held down, place this corner wherever you want and
    release the button.
    To cancel the operation, click on the right mouse button.

    To modify the line width of a box, double click on the box
    and give a new value in the requester.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-B or B

  ARexx call: MENU("Place box")       Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
	      between the words Place and box.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Place triangle" "Drawing menu/Place triangle"
@TOC Drawing

    Selection of this menu is used to draw a triangle, if the menu
    "Filled areas" is marked, it will be filled.

    Triangles can have any line width, as for precedent menus.

    To modify the width of an existing triangle, click twice on it
    with mouse and enter the width you want in the requester.

    @{i}Keyboard shortcut :@{ui} AMIGA-' or '

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"TRIANGLE" LINK TRIANGLE}, @{"DRAWMODE" LINK DRAWMODE}, @{"SETFILL" LINK SETFILL}.

    @{i}ARexx call:@{ui} MENU("Place triangle")     Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
						between the words Place and triangle.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Place ellipse" "Drawing menu/Place ellipse"
@TOC Drawing

    When you select this entry, an ellipse is drawn under the cursor.
    To place an ellipse on the document, move the mouse and when this
    ellipse is where you want it to be, click on the left button.
    You can also modify it's diameters using the cursor keys (UP and
    DOWN for the vertical axis, LEFT and RIGHT for the vertical axis). If
    you use also the SHIFT key, the modification will be faster.
    You can also use the + and - keys to modify the two axis' at the
    same time.

    To modify an ellipse that is on the document, you can use a double
    click on it or click on one of it's axis', near it's border, and
    drag the mouse. If you press the CTRL key while you are performing
    this operation the ellipse will always be drawn as a circle.

    To modify the position of an existing ellipse, click in it's center
    and drag the mouse wherever you want on the document.

    To cancel this mode, choose another placement mode (lines, components
    or connectors...) or click on the right mouse button.

    You can use the menu Rotation for a selected ellipse (Reflection makes
    no sense).

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-E or E

  See also: @{"ELLIPSE" LINK ELLIPSE}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Place ellipse")       Warning: solid space
	    (ALT-SPACE) between Place and ellipse.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Filled areas" "Drawing menu/Filled areas"
@TOC Drawing

    When this menu is marked, rectangles, triangles and ellipses that
    are placed on the sheet are filled, either only the outlines will
    be drawn, using the current width used for lines.

    @{i}Keyboard shortcut :@{ui} AMIGA-" or "

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"SETFILL" LINK SETFILL}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Place arc" "Drawing menu/Place arc"
@TOC Drawing

    When you select this entry, an arc is drawn under the cursor. To place
    this arc on the document, place the cursor where you want and click on
    the left mouse button.
    To cancel this mode, use a click on the right mouse button.

    You can modify it's dimensions using the cursor keys with or without
    the ALT, CTRL and SHIFT keys. With the ALT key you can change the
    radius, with CTRL you can change the angles, the SHIFT key provides
    faster changes.

    To edit an existing arc, you can use a double click to select it and
    use the ALT, CTRL and SHIFT keys in combination with the cursor keys,
    as above. If you none of these qualifier keys is used you can move the
    arc when you use the cursor keys.

    You can also use the menus Rotation and Reflection to modify the
    selected arc.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-§ or §

  See also: @{"ARC" LINK ARC}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Place arc")           Warning: solid space
	  (ALT-SPACE) between Place and arc.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Place junction" "Drawing menu/Place junction"
@TOC Drawing

    When you select this entry a junction is drawn under the cursor.
    To place it, click on the left mouse button.

    To cancel this mode, click on the right mouse button.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-J or J

  See also: @{"JUNCTION" LINK JUNCTION}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Place junction")      Warning: solid space
	  (ALT-SPACE) between Place and junction.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Place text" "Drawing menu/Place text"
@TOC Drawing

    A requester is opened to let you give a text to place on the
    document. If you accept this requester, the text is placed under
    cursor and you can place it where you want, just use the left mouse
    button to place it.
    To cancel this mode, use the right mouse button.

    You can rotate or reflect a text before placing it.

    To modify a text, double click on it and choose a gadget in
    the requester.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-T or T

  See also: @{"WRITE" LINK WRITE}, @{"LINKVAL" LINK LINKVAL}, @{"LINKREF" LINK LINKREF}, @{"LINKLAB" LINK LINKLAB}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Place text")         Warning: solid space
	  (ALT-SPACE) between Place and text.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Place input connector" "Drawing menu/Place input connector"
@TOC Drawing

    A requester is opened to ask you for the connector name. This
    object is attached to its right. The size of this object
    depends on the length of its name. Use the left mouse button
    to place it on the document.
    To cancel this mode, use the right mouse button.

    To modify an existing object of this type double click on it
    with the left mouse button, then choose a gadget in the requester.

    If you want a right pointing arrow, choose the menu @{"Drawing/Reflection" LINK Reflection}.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-< or <

  See also: @{"INPUT" LINK INPUT}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Place input connector")      Warning: solid spaces
	      (ALT-SPACE) between the words.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Place output connector" "Drawing menu/Place output connector"
@TOC Drawing

    A requester is opened to ask you for the connector name. This
    object is attached to its left. The size of this object
    depends on the length of its name. Use the left mouse button
    to place it on the document.
    To cancel this mode, use the right mouse button.

    To modify an existing object of this type double click on it
    with the left mouse button, then choose a gadget in the requester.

    If you want a left pointing arrow, choose the menu @{"Drawing/Reflection" LINK Reflection}.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-> or >

  See also: @{"OUTPUT" LINK OUTPUT}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Place output connector")      Warning: solid spaces
	      (ALT-SPACE) between the words.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Redraw all" "Drawing menu/Redraw all"
@TOC Drawing

    When you select this entry, the complete document is cleared and
    redrawn.
    It's useful after some selections, block moves, or to display the
    grid correctly after some edits...

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-Z or Z

  ARexx call: MENU("Redraw")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Clip" "AmiCAD clips"
@TOC Edition

    Clips are made of any objets, they are defined simply,
    selecting objects then using menus @{"Copy to clip" LINK "Copy to clip"} or @{"Cut to clip" LINK "Cut to clip"}.
    They can be pasted anywhere on the sheet using the @{"Paste menu" LINK "Paste from clip"}.
    They can also be copied on another sheet (the buffer is shared
    between the different tasks).
    They also can be saved in a file and reloaded later.

    Clips have to be done using some simple rules if you want them to be
    easily used. If you want them to be aligned on the grid, the reference
    point of the clip must be on the grid : this point is defined by the
    upper left corner of the objects included in the clip. Of course you
    have to be put the junctions on the grid.

    @{i}Voir aussi :@{ui} @{"CLIPUNIT" LINK CLIPUNIT}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Edition" "Menu Edition"
@TOC "Menus"

    These menus are relative to the objects @{"blocks" LINK Clip} being selected.
    You can select some objects with the mouse, in two ways:
  - clicking in a zone where there is no object, and with the left
    mouse button depressed, drag the mouse. All the objects that are
    present in the rectangle you are drawing will be selected,
  - clicking on an object, this one will be selected. However if
    the menu entry @{"Edition/Multiselection" LINK Multiselection} is not marked,
    only one object at a time can be selected, except if you hold
    one of the SHIFT keys when you click.

    When a block is already selected, you can add objects using one of
    the SHIFT keys while using the left mouse button.

    To select an object that is behind another (to back), select the first
    object, then click on the second while the ALT key is pressed.

    To cancel the selection of an object or of a block, push the CTRL key
    when you use the mouse (with a SHIFT key if necessary...)

    To cancel all the selections, press the ESC key or click twice anywhere
    in the window.

    @{"Copy to clip    " LINK "Copy to clip"}
    @{"Paste from clip " LINK "Paste from clip"}
    @{"Cut to clip     " LINK "Cut to clip"}
    @{"Delete selection" LINK "Delete selection"}
    @{"Clone           " LINK Clone}
    @{"Fix on grid     " LINK "Fix on grid"}
    @{"To Front        " LINK "To Front"}
    @{"To Back         " LINK "To Back"}
    @{"Double size     " LINK "Double size"}
    @{"Divide size     " LINK "Divide size"}
    @{"Scale           " LINK Scale}
    @{"New group       " LINK "New group"}
    @{"Kill group      " LINK "Kill group"}
    @{"Select net      " LINK "Select net"}
    @{"Save clip       " LINK "Save clip"}
    @{"Load clip       " LINK "Load clip"}
    @{"Multiselection  " LINK Multiselection}
    @{"Undo            " LINK Undo}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Copy to clip" "Edition menu/Copy to clip"
@TOC Edition

    This entry handles the copying of the selected objects in memory.
    If it succeeds, the selection is canceled.
    AmiCAD handles 10 buffers (clips), so you can save 10 different
    blocks (see @{"CLIPUNIT" LINK CLIPUNIT}).

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-C (copy) or C

  See also: @{"COPY" LINK COPY}, @{"PASTE" LINK PASTE}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Copy")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Paste from clip" "Edition menu/Paste from clip"
@TOC Edition

    The current clip is copied under the cursor. To place it on the sheet,
    place the cursor where you want using the mouse and click on the left
    mouse button.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-V or V

  See also: @{"CLIPUNIT" LINK CLIPUNIT}, @{"PASTE" LINK PASTE}, @{"COPY" LINK COPY}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Paste")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Cut to clip" "Edition menu/Cut to clip"
@TOC Edition

    This entry deletes all the selected objects, the block is copied into
    the current clip.

    Warning: This function can modify the numbers of the objects present
	     on the document.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-X or X

  See also: @{"CLIPUNIT" LINK CLIPUNIT}, @{"PASTE" LINK PASTE}, @{"COPY" LINK COPY}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Cut")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Delete selection" "Edition menu/Delete selection"
@TOC Edition

    This entry deletes all the selected objects.

    Warning: This function can modify the numbers of the objects present
	     on the document.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-Y, Y or DEL

  ARexx call: MENU("Delete")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Clone" "Edition menu/Clone"
@TOC Edition

    This entry clones the selected objects. You can obtain the same
    result using first the @{"Copy" LINK "Copy to clip"} menu, then the @{"Paste" LINK "Paste from clip"} menu.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-TAB or TAB

  ARexx call: MENU("Clone")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Fix on grid" "Edition menu/Fix on grid"
@TOC Edition

    This menu fixes all the selected objects on the grid. This entry
    is useful to align some objects. The point of the objects that
    is fixed on the grid is the upper left corner.

    Groups are not correctly handled by this menu entry.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-! or !

  ARexx call: MENU("Fix")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "To Front" "Edition menu/To Front"
@TOC Edition

    All the selected objects are placed before the others, so when
    you click on one of them you can reach them easily.

    Note: you can reach an object placed behind another one using
    the ALT key when clicking on them, the first time you'll get
    the first object, the second one you'll get the second object.

    Warning: This function modifies the objects numbering.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-M or M

  ARexx call: MENU("To front")    Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
	  between the words To and front.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "To Back" "Edition menu/To Back"
@TOC Edition

    All the selected objects are placed at the end of the list.
    So when you click on them they are not selected if there are
    other objects in the same location.

    Warning: This function modifies the objects numbering.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-D or D

  ARexx call: MENU("To Back")     Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
	  between the words To and Back.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Double size" "Edition Menu/Double size"
@TOC Edition

    The size of the selected elements is doubled. You can also
    use this function to double the current object under the
    cursor, or while placing an object (from a clip).

    The objects can't go outside the window to permit to the function
    to succeed.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-+ or +

  See also: @{"SETSCALE" LINK SETSCALE}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Double size")     Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
	    between the words Double and Size

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Divide size" "Edition Menu/Divide size"
@TOC Edition

    The size of all the selected objects is halved. The size of these
    objects have to be a multiple of two (scale of 2, 4, 6...)
    This function can also divide the size of the currrent object placed
    under the cursor, or while placing an object (from a clip).

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-- or -

  See also: @{"SETSCALE" LINK SETSCALE}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Divide size")     Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
	   between the words Divide and size.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Scale" "Menu Édition/Scale"
@TOC Edition

    This menu changes the size of the selected objects giving the
    user the possibility to choose the ration of the scale operation.
    If this ration is greater than 100, the size of the block
    becomes greater, while it becomes smaller if the size is lower
    than 100.

    @{I}Keyboard shortcut :@{UI} AMIGA-# or #

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"SETSCALE" LINK SETSCALE}.

    @{I}ARexx call :@{UI} MENU("Scale")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "New group" "Edition Menu/New group"
@TOC Edition

    All the selected objects are grouped together. Then you can select
    all of them by clicking on one. The wires connected to a group can
    be used like a component, when this group is moved.
    Grouping the objects of a clip is a good way to create clips that
    look like components.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-{ or {

  ARexx call: MENU("New group")       Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
	      between the words New and group.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Kill group" "Edition Menu/Kill group"
@TOC Edition

    The selected group is deleted. All the objects that where
    in a group are unselected.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-} or }

  ARexx call: MENU("Kill group")      Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
	      between the words Kill and group.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Select net" "Menu Edition/Select net"
@TOC Edition

    This menu is used to select a net, defined by the wires that are
    connected together. Two wires that have a commun point are on
    the same net only if they are connected with a junction.
    If the net have a label, all the objects using the same label
    will be also selected. If the net is connected to a ground, all
    the other wires that are also connected to a same type ground
    will also be selected (id. for power lines with the same reference).
    The function works for normal wires and double width lines.
    You can select either a wire or a label before calling the menu,
    but not a ground or a power line.

    @{b}Warning :@{ub} this function can modify some nets, if two lines have
    the same direction, and have a common part, without any other
    connection, this two lines will be merged using only one line.

  @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-M or M

  @{i}ARexx call:@{ui} MENU("Select net")    Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
				between the words Select and Net.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Save clip" "Menu Edition/Save clip"
@TOC Edition

    This menu is used to save the selected block in a file, this
    file is selected with the asl.library requester.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-W or W

  See also: @{"SAVECLIP" LINK SAVECLIP}, @{"LOADCLIP" LINK LOADCLIP} functions.

  ARexx call: MENU("Save clip")       Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
	      between the words Save and clip.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Load clip" "Menu Edition/Load clip"
@TOC Edition

    This menu is used to read a block that was previously saved
    in a file (selected with the asl.library requester). If the
    operation succeeds the block is displayed under the mouse
    cursor and is moved with it. Use a left mouse button click
    to place it, or on the right mouse button to cancel the
    operation.

    The anchor point of a clip is the upper left corner of the
    box defined by all the objects in this clip. If you create
    clips with this point on the grid, their placement will be
    easier later.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-L or L

  See also: @{"LOADCLIP" LINK LOADCLIP}, @{"SAVECLIP" LINK SAVECLIP} functions.

  ARexx call: MENU("Load clip")       Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
	      between the words Load and clip.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Multiselection" "Menu Edition/Multiselection"
@TOC Edition

    When this entry is marked, you can select all the objects
    you want, clicking on them without using a SHIFT key.

    You have to select this menu to toggle its state.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-*

  No ARexx call is possible.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Undo" "Menu Edition/Undo"
@TOC Edition

    This menu can be used to cancel the last operation that was
    done on the document in memory. But the ARexx scripts or
    ARexx functions will be canceled only if the @{"SAVEALL" LINK SAVEALL} macro
    is used in them.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-U or U

  ARexx call: MENU("Undo")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Scripts" "Scripts menu"
@TOC "Menus"

    @{"Call script" LINK "Call script"}       Calls a selected ARexx script.
    @{"ARexx...   " LINK "ARexx..."}       20 Programmable ARexx scripts.

    @{"Scripts description" LINK ARexxScripts}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Macros" "Macros menu"
@TOC "Menus"

    These menus are used for @{"macro-commands" LINK "Ecriture commandes"} and
    can be used to add commands linked to new menus, they are saved while
    @{"saving preferences" LINK "Startup prefs"}.

    @{"Direct mode" LINK Direct}       Ask for a command, execute it
    @{"Add menu   " LINK "Add menu"}       Add a menu
    @{"Edit label " LINK "Edit label"}       Edit a menu label
    @{"Edit macro " LINK "Edit macro"}       Edit a macro assoiated to a menu
    @{"Remove menu" LINK "Remove menu"}       Remove one or several menus
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Direct" "Macros Menu/Mode direct"
@TOC "Macros"

    This menu allows the entry of a @{"macro-command" LINK "Ecriture commandes"}, then its execution.
    It should be noted that these programmed sequences are backed up in the file
    AmiCAD.keys, using the menu @{"Preferences/Programming keys" LINK Programming}. Those are then
    reloaded during each launching of the program.

    The requester have a cell to the left, when you click on it, a new
    requester will allow you to select a function between all the
    available functions, including the @{"user defined functions" LINK DEF}, at the
    end of the list, you can also select a function in this list
    and press the Help key to open the AmigaGuide description for
    this function.

    You can cause the display of a result of a command by beginning the text
    specifying this command with the equal sign (=).

  Examples:
      =4*95	 displays the result of the multiplication (4 times 95)
      =FIRSTSEL  displays the number of the first selected object

    Warning : you can't undo the operation done by a macro, except
    if you are using the @{"SAVEALL" LINK SAVEALL} function.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-; ou ;

  See also: functions @{"EXEC" LINK EXEC}, @{"MACRO" LINK MACRO}, @{"MAP" LINK MAP}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Mode direct")         Warning: space "solid"
				  (ALT-SPACE) between Mode and direct.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Add menu" "Macros Menu/Add menu"
@TOC Macros

    This menu allows the user to add menus defined to his
    convenience.To add a new entry, select this menu, then
    enter the macro-command to assiocate to this menu (you
    can enter any function or combination of functions,
    including a call to an ARexx script using the @{"CALL" LINK CALL}
    function), if you valid the requester, you have to
    enter the name that will appear in the menu, when
    this requester is validated you have to choose the
    place of the new menu in the menu list.

    Warning : you can't enter a definition or a name that
    are already existing or you'll get an error.

    @{b}Separators@{ub}
    To define a separator, enter an empty string for the macro
    command and enter the name BAR in the second requester.

    @{b}Saving menus@{ub}
    The definitions of the menus are saved using the @{"Preferences" LINK "Startup prefs"}
    menu, clicking the Save button. Definitions are saved in the
    @{"AmiCAD.prefs" LINK Fichiers_Configuration} file, they will be loaded the next time AmiCAD
    will be running.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Edit label" "Macros menu/Edit label"
@TOC Macros

    This menu is used to modify the name associated to a
    menu entry. Just select the entry to change and validate
    the requester with the new name.

    The label "BAR" is used to have a separator between two
    menus entries.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Edit macro" "Macros menu/Edit macro"
@TOC Macros

    This menu allows the user to modify the macro-command associated
    to a menu entry. You have to select the entry in the list, then
    change the definition of the macro-command.

    @{"Macro-commands" LINK "Ecriture commandes"} can use all available @{"functions" LINK Fonctions}.
    To call an ARexx @{"script" LINK Script}, use the @{"CALL" LINK CALL} function.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Remove menu" "Menu Utilisateur/Supprimer menu"
@TOC Macros

    This menu is used to delete a previously defined menu.
    Just select the menu to delete in the list... and bye
    bye !
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Call script" "Menu Macros/Call script"
@TOC "Macros"

    This menu allows the entry of a ARexx command, (give the name of the
    @{"script" LINK Script }, the extension "AmiCAD" is not obligatory).

  Keyboard shortcut:  AMIGA -, or ,

  See also:  function @{"CALL" LINK CALL }.

  ARexx call: MENU("Appel script")       Warning: space "solid"
	  (ALT-SPACE)  between Appel and script.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "ARexx..." "Menu Macros/ARexx..."
@TOC "Macros"

    These 20 menuitems are used to define 20 commands able to be launched
    by the selection of the corresponding menu.
    At the time of the first call of the menu, the user must define
    it's command, by giving the name of the script to execute, (without the
    path).
    The calls which will follow allow the call of the defined @{"script" LINK Script}.
    The name of the script then appears in the menu.  The 20 definitions
    can be saved to the file "AmiCAD.prefs", and be reloaded automatically
    at the execution of the AmiCAD program.
    These menus can be redefined while pressing one of the SHIFT keys
    during menu selection.

    Note that the @{b}editing of a defined script@{ub} can be made in an automatic
    way in a new window by calling the menu while @{i}pressing the CTRL key,@{ui}
    (the name must naturally have been defined before).
    The program then launches the ARexx script EditScript.AmiCAD, passing to
    it the name of this script in argument.
    This script, (EditScript), must be adapted to the editor which you use
    and to your installation, it's written for my text editor, Amitex.

    The command must comprise the name of the script to be executed, (always
    without the extension "AmiCAD").
    The name can only be a maximum of 11 characters long.
    It is not possible to transmit parameters to the script.
    The communications with ARexx are made thanks to the @{"port" LINK Port} AmiCAD.0,
    (or AmiCAD.1, AmiCAD.2... AmiCAD.999 if several tasks are running at the same
    time).
    Use the command port=ADDRESS() to find the port name, if necessary.

    @{i}Short cuts keyboard:@{ui} AMIGA-0 with AMIGA-9

    @{i}See also:@{ui} function @{"CALL" LINK CALL}.

    No possible ARexx call for these menus, use function CALL.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Port" "Port ARexx"
@TOC "Macros"

    The program normally opens a port of communication with the ARexx
    interpreter during it's launching, this port is called AmiCAD.0, for
    the first task being launched. If several windows are opened, the
    second port is called AmiCAD.1, then AmiCAD.2 for the following one,
    and so (AmiCAD.999 is the limit...)
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Preferences" "Menu Preferences"
@TOC "Menus"

    This series of menus makes it possible to save certain adjustments to the
    program in the files AmiCAD.prefs and AmiCAD.keys.	These files are saved
    in the current directory.
    These files are read automatically at program execution, in order to
    reload the adjustments desired by the user.
    These two files are in ASCII format and can thus be viewed and even
    modified using a text editor.
    You can in fact, create mini-configuration files containing only part of
    the configuration, like the palette for example, (see the AmiCAD.palette
    file for an example).

  @{"Auto scroll     " LINK "Auto scroll"}
  @{"Backup file     " LINK "Backup file"}
  @{"Save icon       " LINK "Save icon"}
  @{"Pull lines      " LINK "Pull lines"}
  @{"Display grid    " LINK "Display grid"}
  @{"Full name       " LINK "Full name"}
  @{"Display zoom    " LINK "Display zoom"}
  @{"Sheet size      " LINK "Sheet size"}
  @{"Startup prefs   " LINK "Startup prefs"}
  @{"Keys            " LINK Programming}
  @{"New bar         " LINK "New bar"}
  @{"Load toolbar    " LINK "Load toolbar"}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Auto scroll" "Menu Preferences/Auto scroll"
@TOC Preferences

    When this item is enabled, if the cursor arrives at an edge of the
    current work window, the contents is automatically scrolled if
    necessary.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

    No possible ARexx call for these menus.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Backup file" "Menu Preferences/Backup file"
@TOC Preferences

    When this item is enabled, a backup file with the extension ".bis", is
    created when the sheet is saved.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

  See also:  function @{"SAVECOPY" LINK SAVECOPY }.

    No possible ARexx call for this menu.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Save icon" "Menu Preferences/Save icon"
@TOC Preferences

    If this item is enabled an icon is created when the sheet is saved.
    The name of the program appears in the Default Tool field.	The icon
    used is the default "Project" icon, stored in directory ENV:Sys.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

    See also:  function @{"SAVEICON" LINK SAVEICON }.

    No possible ARexx call for this menu.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Pull lines" "Menu Preferences/Pull lines"
@TOC Preferences

    If this item is enabled, during the relocation of one or more
    components by using the mouse, any wires connected to these
    components will be also moved.
    When this mode is on, a L is displayed in the title bar.

    Warning:  This operation takes place only after having released
	      these components in their new position.

    Keyboard shortcut:	AMIGA-F or F

    See also : @{"SETPULL" LINK SETPULL}

    ARexx call:  MENU("Pull")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Display grid" "Menu Preferences/Display grid"
@TOC Preferences

    If this item is enabled, a grid is displayed on the screen.  The step
    used is that defined in the menu @{"Drawing/Grid size" LINK "Grid size"}.
    The screen is updated after the call of the menu.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

    No possible ARexx call for this menu.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Full name" "Menu Preferences/Full name"
@TOC Preferences

    If enabled, this menuitem will display the complete name of the
    document in the @{"titlebar" LINK "Barre de titre"}.
    If it is not, the name is displayed without the path, this allows
    more space for other indicators in the titlebar, the co-ordinates
    of the cursor in particular, when the window is not sufficiently
    wide or when the complete name is very long (multiple (sub)-
    directories)).
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Display zoom" "Preferences menu/Display zoom"
@TOC Preferences

    This menu set is used to choose the scale ratio and the
    scrolling of the window contents.
    The ration can be set to 25% to 1000%.

    A value of the ratio equal to @{B}100%@{UB} gives a normal view.
@{B}	1@{UB}).


    @{"4- Full height    " LINK 4-}
    @{"0- Full width     " LINK 0-}
    @{"1- Normal scale   " LINK 1-}
    @{"2- Box            " LINK 2-}
    @{"5- Center on point" LINK 5-}
    @{"6- Zoom in        " LINK 6-}
    @{"9- Zoom out       " LINK 9-}
    @{"3- Numeric        " LINK 3-}


    @{I}See also :@{UI} {"ZOOM" LINK ZOOM} function.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "0-" "Preferences menu/Display zoom/0- Full width"
@TOC Display zoom

    This menu is used to make the current window as large as the
    screen width.

    @{b}Keyboard shortcut :@{ub} key 0 of the numeric keyboard
@ENDNODE
@NODE "4-" "Preferences menu/Display zoom/4- Full height"
@TOC Display zoom

    This menu is used to make the current window as large as the
    screen height.

    @{b}Keyboard shortcut :@{ub} key 4 of the numeric keyboard
@ENDNODE
@NODE "1-" "Preferences menu/Display zoom/1- Normal scale"
@TOC Display zoom

    This menu is used to have a normal display ration (100%).

    @{b}Keyboard shortcut :@{ub} key 1 of the numeric keyboard
@ENDNODE
@NODE "2-" "Preferences menu/Display zoom/2- Box"
@TOC Display zoom

    This menu is used to select a zone in the window that will
    be displayed using the correct ratio to fit in the full
    window. You have to use the left mouse button (drag it
    while the button is pressed) to define the zone.

    You can cancel the operation clicking on the right mouse
    button or pressing any key.

    @{b}Keyboard shortcut :@{ub} key 2 of the numeric keyboard
@ENDNODE
@NODE "5-" "Preferences menu/Display zoom/5- Center on point"
@TOC Display zoom

    Using this menu change the center of the display. Just
    click on the point where you want to have the center.

    @{b}Keyboard shortcut :@{ub} key 5 of the numeric keyboard
@ENDNODE
@NODE "6-" "Preferences menu/Display zoom/6- Zoom in"
@TOC Display zoom

    The display ratio is multiplicated by 2 (if lower than 1000%).

    @{b}Keyboard shortcut :@{ub} key 6 of the numeric keyboard
@ENDNODE
@NODE "9-" "Preferences menu/Display zoom/9- Zoom out"
@TOC Display zoom

    The display ratio is divided by 2 (if greater than 25%).

    @{b}Keyboard shortcut :@{ub} key 9 of the numeric keyboard
@ENDNODE
@NODE "3-" "Preferences menu/Display zoom/3- Numeric"
@TOC Display zoom

    Selecting this menu opens a requester where the user can
    enter the zoom ratio used to display the objects in the
    current window.

    @{b}Keyboard shortcut :@{ub} key 3 of the numeric keyboard
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Sheet size" "Menu Preferences/Sheet size"
@TOC Preferences

    This menuitem makes it possible to define the width and the height of
    the worksheet. Be carefull when the new size is smaller, if objects
    can't fit in the new window, they will be loosed for ever (this
    operation can't be canceled).

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

    See also: function @{"DIMSHEET" LINK DIMSHEET}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Dimensions")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Startup prefs" "Preferences Menu/Startup prefs"
@TOC Preferences

    This menu is used to choose some options, it uses a Reaction
    requester.
    Three tabs are present:
	@{"Display" LINK Display} screen mode, font...
	@{"Program" LINK Program} menu state at startup...
	@{"Palette" LINK Palette} objects colors...

    The selected settings can be saved in the AmiCAD.prefs file,
    used (for opening new documents) or canceled using the buttons
    located at the bottom of the requester.
    The AmiCAD.prefs file can also be edited with a text editor,
    it's loaded when the program is launched.

    Nota: saving the preferences makes also the scripts names
    used in the Script menu to be saved (see @{"scripts" LINK Scripts} and @{"ARexx macros" LINK Macros}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Display "Preferences requester/Display tab"
@TOC "Startup prefs"

    This tab makes it posible to choose :
	- the display mode (you can select the screen mode
	in a requester).
	- the font used for the screen and for requesters.
	- the toolbar that will be loaded when running the
	program.
	- the default size of the new documents.
	- the dimensions and position of the window.
	The "Read actual values" set the values to the
	values used for the current window.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Program "Preferences requester/Program tab"
@TOC "Startup prefs"

    This tab can set several options of the program at startup :
	- Place reference: see @{"Drawing/Place reference" LINK "Place reference"} menu
	- Place value: see @{"Drawing/Place value" LINK "Place value"} menu
	- Place pins numbers: see @{"Drawing menu/Place pins numbers" LINK "Place pins numbers"} menu
	- Auto scroll: see @{"Preferences menu/Auto scroll" LINK "Auto scroll"} menu
	- Display grid: see @{"Preferences menu/Display grid" LINK "Display grid"} menu
	- Snap on grid: see @{"Drawing/Snap on grid" LINK "Snap on grid"} menu
	- Grid size: see @{"Drawing/Grid size" LINK "Grid size"} menu
	- Requesters: select the position of the requesters, in the center of
	the current window, under the mouse pointer.

	- Multiselection: see @{"Edition/Multiselection" LINK Multiselection} menu
	- Backup file: see @{"Preferences/Backup file" LINK "Backup file"} menu
	- Sauve icon: see @{"Preferences/Sauve icon" LINK "Save icon"} menu
	- Pull wires: see @{"Preferences/Pull wires" LINK "Pull wires"} menu
	- Full name: see @{"Preferences/Full name" LINK "Full name"} menu
	- Orthogonal mode: see @{"Drawing/Orthogonal mode" LINK Orthogonal mode} menu
	- Continuous drawing: see @{"Drawing/Continuous drawing" LINK "Continuous drawing"} menu
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Palette" "Preferences requester/Palette tab"
@TOC "Startup prefs"

    This tab makes it possible to choose the colours of the screen used by
    AmiCAD.  Note that these colours are saved in the configuration file.

    These colors are used to display the objects in the windows :
    - color 1: window background (defaults to white)
    - color 2: grid (black)
    - color 3: special lines, ellipses, arcs (orange)
    - color 4: components (blue)
    - color 5: wires, junctions (dark blue)
    - color 6: input connectors
    - color 7: output connectors (clear blue)
    - color 8: references (brown)
    - color 9: values (green)
    - color 10: texts (dark blue)
    - color 11: selected objects (red)
    Warning:  Do not use a too dark colour for colour 1, black for
    example, because then the cursor used to place wires would become
    invisible...
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Programming" "Preferences/Programming keys menu"
@TOC Preferences

    This menu is used to programm the function keys. To save the
    definitions of the keys, use the Save button (they will be
    saved in the @{"AmiCAD.keys" LINK Fichiers_Configuration} file).
    The Use button makes the definitions available for the current
    session, but the definitions are not saved on disk.

    The button located at the bottom left corner of the requester
    is used to program other keys (letters, numbers...), enter the
    key to define in the cell.

    The keys defined using the @{"MAP" LINK MAP} function are also available in
    this requester, they will also be saved in the AmiCAD.keys file.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "New bar" "Menu Preferences/New bar"
@TOC Preferences

    This menu is used to create a new @{"toolbar" LINK ToolBars}.
    A new task is created to do this job, so you can
    continue to work in the current document.

    See also : @{"EDITBAR" LINK EDITBAR} function.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Load toolbar" "Preferences menu/load toolbar"
@TOC Preferences

    This menu is used to select a toolbar. You can use several
    toolbars at the same moment.

    How to @{"create" LINK ToolBars} a toolbar, @{"TOOLBAR" LINK TOOLBAR} function.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Keys" "Use of the keyboard"
@TOC "MAIN"

    HELP

    Launches the program AmigaGuide, this one loads the help file
    AmiCAD.guide.
    This guide must be in the directory where the AmiCAD program is located,
    or at the place specified by the tooltype @{"HELPFILE" LINK HELPFILE}.

    ESC

    Close requesters

    ENTER

    Validation of requesters

    @{b}Edit commands@{ub}

    CTRL:
    Allows deselection of elements if used at the same time as the left
    button of the mouse during the selection.

    ALT:
    Allows to select an object that is located on the back, use it
    with the left mouse button when clicking on an object.

    Note : you can program any function key using the @{"MAP" LINK MAP} function,
    the @{"Preferences/Keys" LINK Programming} menu or directly by editing the AmiCAD.keys
    file using a text editor.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Fichiers_Configuration "Format of the configuration files"
@TOC Preferences

    The files AmiCAD.prefs and AmiCAD.keys are ASCII format files, they
    can thus be viewed, (and also modified), using a simple text editor.
    Their format follows some elementary rules however.

    Each one of these two files starts with a heading which should not be
    changed, it in particular includes the version number of these files,
    AmiCAD recognizes only the version in force for a given AmiCAD
    version. Version 1.2 of AmiCAD uses the headings:
      "AmiCADPrefs 1.1" for the AmiCAD.prefs file,
      "AmiCADKeys 1.0"  for the AmiCAD.keys file.

    The AmiCAD.prefs file then includes several paragraphs, these
    paragraphs can be removed to create a particular configuration,
    including for example only one palette of colours (AmiCAD.palette
    file for example).

    Each one of these paragraphs begins  with texts placed between
    2 hooks ([Menus_ARexx], [Screen], [Palette] and [Mode]), these
    texts are followed by  several lines including each  different
    information. Whole or part of these lines can be removed.

    Each paragraph is defined as follow :
	[Menus_ARexx] : define the 20 programmables menus of the
	    @{"ARexx" LINK ARexx...} menu. The script name have to be written
	    on the command line. If the line is deleted the menu entry
	    will be empty. You can't enter more than 11 chars.
	[Screen] : define the mode of the screen used by AmiCAD (ModeID),
	    its name (Title), and the font used to display the menus and
	    requesters (Font).
	[Window] : define the position (X and Y) and the dimensions
	    (Width and Heigth) of the windows used by the program@{" " LINK Display}
	[Colors] : define the @{"colors" LINK Palette} used to display the
	    objects.
	[Doc] : define the default dimensions of a new document opened
	    by AmiCAD (document size in @{"Display" LINK Display}).
	[Mode] : define the @{"program" LINK Program} settings at startup.
	[User_Menus] : the definitions of the @{"Macros" LINK "Add menu"} menu are
	    saved in this paragraph.


    In the  same way the  AmiCAD.keys  file includes one paragraph
    [Macros] for each key. You can add or remove  lines in this paragraph,
    to suit your configuration. Don't forget to end the paragraph with
    the [EndMacro] line.

    Warning: The words located on the left of the signs = must be written
    just as they are (no major/minor changes).
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Ecriture commandes" "Writing a line of command(s)"
@TOC "Macros"

    The macro-commands can be carried out in local mode or by the
    intermediary of an @{"ARexx script" LINK Script}.  You can refer to the
    scripts given, for example, in the ARexx directory.  These must have the
    extension ".AmiCAD" in their name.

    Each one of these macro-commands can call one of the ARexx functions, or
    even several.  Some of them require one or more arguments, finally the
    majority of them return a result.  The program also makes it possible
    to handle @{"variables" LINK Variable }, (both numerical or character
    string type).  Also you can define your own functions.

    The call of a function is done by giving its name, followed by of one
    or more arguments, surrounded by brackets, possibly separated by commas.

    The traditional mathematical @{"operators" LINK Operators} are of course available.

    It should be noted that you can place a comment in a macro comprising a
    mathematical expression by using the apostrophe seen previously.

  Example:
      DELETE(FIRSTSEL) 'Deletion of the first selected element

    Lastly, you can place several function calls on the same line, by
    separating them with a colon.

  Example:
      SETSCALE(FIRSTSEL,200,2000):SETSCALE(NEXTSEL(FIRSTSEL),200,200)
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Operators" "Available mathematics operators"
@TOC Macros

	  Operator	    signs	priority

      rise with a power:      ^ 	   10
      division: 	      / 	    9
      multiplication:	      * 	    9
      modulo:		      % 	    9
      addition: 	      + 	    8
      subtraction:	      - 	    8
      AND logic:	      & 	    6
      OR exclusive	      ? 	    5
      OR logic		      | 	    4
      assignment	      = 	    2

    This last operator (=) can be used to affect @{"variables" LINK Variable }.

  Example:
      A=2, assigns value 2 to variable A.

    It should be noted that writing A=B=3 is not allowed, it will involve an error
    message "Impossible Assignment".  Rather, write A=3:B=3.

      Other operators:

      shift on the left:     <<
      shift on the right:    >>

    These two operators have a priority equal to 7.

      higher test:	      > 	 higher or equal test:	   >=
      lower test:	      < 	 lower or equal test:	   <=
      inequality test:	     <> 	 test equality: 	   ==

    The tests return the value 1 if they are true, 0 in the othercases.
    Their priority is equal to 3.

    There is a particular operator which in fact isn't one, it is the sign
    ':',  this allows the separation of two statements, (or more), in order
    to be able to place several assignments of @{"variables" LINK Variable} in the same
    function.
    Thus you can place A=2:B=3:C=0 in only one command instead of using three
    of them.  The returned result is then that of the last operation
    carried out, (0 in this example).  This possibility can also be of
    interest for the function FOR, (see further), in order to carry out
    multiple initializations at the beginning of a loop.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Variable "The variables"
@TOC Macros

    The variables handled by AmiCAD can be of two types: @{b}numeric@{ub }
    or @{b}character strings@{ub }.  The type is selected at the time
    of the assignment, it cannot then be changed, unless the variable
    is reinitialized, (see function @{"INIT" LINK INIT}).

    To assign a value to a variable it is enough to follow its name
    with the sign = and the value to be assigned to it.

  Examples:
      A = 1
      B2 = "text string"
      A2 = "First"+B2     gives "First text string"

    The @{"character strings" LINK "Chaînes de caractčres"} must be framed by quotation marks
    if they are constants. Numerical @{"valeurs" LINK Numbers} are limited to integers,
    (long), use ARexx to handle real numbers.

    The names of variables can include from 1 to 21 characters, they must
    begin with a letter, the following characters are able to be letters
    (accentuated or not), numbers or the character _.

  Examples of valid names:
      TEST
      TYPE_DONNÉE
      LINE1

    Note that the program normally converts the names of functions and
    variables into capital letters during input, therefore there will not
    be a difference between two names like variable and VARIABLE, (or even
    Variable), however in an @{"ARexx script" LINK Script}, preferably use
    capital letters because the strings resulting from the interpreter are
    not converted, and inevitably the program will then differentiate
    between names written in lower case and/or upper case.

    Warning:  The variables are not usable directly with ARexx, they are
    internal to the program AmiCAD and the ARexx interpreter has it's own
    variables.	It is however possible to simply return a value of
    variable to the interpreter by giving it's name:

  Example:
      'NAME_VARIABLE'; v=result

    The contents of variable NAME_VARIABLE is thus transferred in the variable
    ARexx v.
    It is often advantageous to use internal variables with AmiCAD because
    their processing is faster, in addition it can avoid the sending of
    certain messages between the interpreter and the program, which
    involves an enormous speed profit.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Numbers" "Numeric Variables"
@TOC Maths

    The numbers handled by AmiCAD are limited to integers.  These are signed
    32 bit long integers.
    The maximum value is 2^31-1 (2147483647) and the minimum value -2^31
    (-2147483648).
    Use the capacities of the ARexx interpreter to handle numbers in floating
    point.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Chaînes de caractčres" "Character string variables"
@TOC Variable

    The character strings can include an unspecified number of characters,
    (theoretically limited only by the memory size of your microcomputer),
    while starting with null strings which do not include any character.
    To define a character string, you must frame it's contents by two
    quotation marks.
    If this string includes itself one or more quotation marks, those must
    be doubled.

  Examples:
      "This is a character string"
      ""
      "It is a quotation mark "" !"
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Script" "Structure of ARexx scripts"

    ARexx scripts are ASCII files, conforming to a format allowing their
    interpretation by this software.  They can include all the functions
    specific to ARexx and its libraries, (I refer you to their documentation
    for more precise details), like all the commands supported by the
    program AmiCAD, (a hundred, plus any functions defined by yourself).

    @{b}Location@{ub}
    These scripts must be located in the AmiCAD/ARexx directory.  It is
    advised to name them with the AmiCAD extension, but it is not obligatory.

    @{b}Format@{ub}
    These scripts must always start with a remark included between the
    characters /* and */, as in language C.

    The AmiCAD commands must imperatively appear in upper case.  They
    are the same ones as those which are used in @{"local mode" LINK Direct}, however
    their analysis by ARexx requires some precautions, thus these commands
    must imperatively be framed by apostrophes (') or quotation marks, in
    order to differentiate them from the internal functions within ARexx.

    @{b}Example@{ub}
    The following structure is recommended for these scripts:

/* This file gives you an example of structure possible for a
script called by AmiCAD */

options results     /* essential to recover the results of the macros */

signal on error     /* for the interception of errors */
signal on syntax

/* your program must be located in this zone */

exit

/* Processing of errors, interruption of the program */
syntax:
error = RC
'MESSAGE("Syntax error"+CHR(10)+"in line 'SIGL'"+CHR(10)+"'errortext(error)'")'
exit

error:
'MESSAGE("Error in line 'SIGL'")'
exit

    This example exists already ready in the ARexx directory, under the
    name @{b}New.AmiCAD@{ub }.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ARexxScripts "ARexx scripts description"
@TOC Main

    Documentations are written for the version number of the script
    specified in its description. Note that some scripts are only
    calling other scripts with french names.

    Modification or creation of objects
	@{"     Align    " LINK Aligner.AmiCAD}        @{"  RoundedBox  " LINK BoîteArrondie.AmiCAD}
	@{"   TextFrame  " LINK CadrerTexte.AmiCAD}        @{"    Center    " LINK Centrer.AmiCAD}
	@{"EditComponents" LINK EditComponents.AmiCAD}        @{" EditConnect  " LINK EditConnect.AmiCAD}
	@{"   EditString " LINK EditString.AmiCAD}        @{"  ImportText  " LINK ImportTexte.AmiCAD}
	@{"   InitObjets " LINK InitObjets.AmiCAD}        @{"  UPPERCASE   " LINK Majuscules.AmiCAD}
	@{"   PutConnect " LINK PutConnect.AmiCAD}        @{"  Duplicate   " LINK Recopier.AmiCAD}
	@{"    AddRefs   " LINK Référencer.AmiCAD}        @{"  SearchLib   " LINK SearchLib.AmiCAD}
	@{"  SelectParts " LINK SelectParts.AmiCAD}        @{"  UnderLine   " LINK Souligner.AmiCAD}
	@{"   DragLines  " LINK TirerTraits.AmiCAD}        @{"   Rotate     " LINK Tourner.AmiCAD}
	@{"      Zoom    " LINK Zoom.AmiCAD}

    Simulation (spice)
	@{"   AmiPlot    " LINK AmiPlot.AmiCAD}        @{"ChoixSignaux " LINK ChoixSignaux.AmiCAD}
	@{" ControlNets  " LINK ControlNets.AmiCAD}        @{" CreateNets  " LINK CreateNets.AmiCAD}
	@{"  DefSignal   " LINK DefSignal.AmiCAD}        @{" GuideSpice  " LINK GuideSpice.AmiCAD}
	@{"   LinkNets   " LINK LinkNets.AmiCAD}        @{"   MarkPins  " LINK MarkPins.AmiCAD}
	@{"  Nets2File   " LINK Nets2File.AmiCAD}        @{"NewCreateNets" LINK NewCreateNets.AmiCAD}
	@{"PurgeTempFiles" LINK PurgeTempFiles.AmiCAD}        @{"  SaveNets   " LINK SaveNets.AmiCAD}
	@{"   SelectNet  " LINK SelectNet.AmiCAD}        @{"  Simulate   " LINK Simulate.AmiCAD}
	@{" Simulation   " LINK Simulation.AmiCAD}        @{" SimulUtils  " LINK SimulUtils.AmiCAD}
	@{"   TestNets   " LINK TestNets.AmiCAD}        @{" TraceSpice  " LINK TracerSpice.AmiCAD}
	@{"   Analyse    " LINK TypeAnalyse.AmiCAD}        @{"   VisuNet   " LINK VisuNet.AmiCAD}
	@{"DisplayNetList" LINK VisuNetlist.AmiCAD}        @{"  VisuNets   " LINK VisuNets.AmiCAD}

    AmiPCB (creating printed circuit boards)
	@{"    AmiPCB    " LINK AmiPCB.AmiCAD}        @{"   CAD2PCB   " LINK CAD2PCB.AmiCAD}
	@{"  CheckNoPCB  " LINK CheckNoPCB.AmiCAD}        @{"  MarkPins   " LINK MarkPins.AmiCAD}
	@{" ReadPCBClip  " LINK ReadPCBClip.AmiCAD}        @{"  SetMasks   " LINK SetMasks.AmiCAD}
	@{"ShowNoPCBMask " LINK ShowNoPCBMask.AmiCAD}        @{"ShowPCBMasks " LINK ShowPCBMasks.AmiCAD}

    Format conversion
	@{"  Save2GIF    " LINK Save2GIF.AmiCAD}        @{" Conv2META  " LINK Conv2META.AmiCAD}

    Others
	@{"     Calc     " LINK Calc.AmiCAD}        @{"  WriteChar  " LINK Caractčre.AmiCAD}
	@{"  Cartouche   " LINK Cartouche.AmiCAD}        @{"  ChargeRC   " LINK ChargeRC.AmiCAD}
	@{"ChercherTexte " LINK ChercherTexte.AmiCAD}        @{" ChoixFormat " LINK ChoixFormat.AmiCAD}
	@{"     Date     " LINK Date.AmiCAD}        @{" EditScript  " LINK EditScript.AmiCAD}
	@{"   FindPort   " LINK FindPort.AmiCAD}        @{"  FixQuotes  " LINK FixQuotes.AmiCAD}
	@{"     Grid     " LINK Grille.AmiCAD}        @{"ImportClip1.0" LINK ImportClip1.0.AmiCAD}
	@{"ImportFile1.0 " LINK ImportFile1.0.AmiCAD}        @{"  Karnaugh   " LINK Karnaugh.AmiCAD}
	@{"    MapKey    " LINK MapKey.AmiCAD}        @{"  NewScript  " LINK NewScript.AmiCAD}
	@{"  NewWindow   " LINK NewWindow.AmiCAD}        @{"Nomenclature " LINK Nomenclature.AmiCAD}
	@{"Redimensionner" LINK Redimensionner.AmiCAD}        @{"  AutoSauve  " LINK SauverAuto.AmiCAD}
	@{"  TruthTable  " LINK TableVérité.AmiCAD}
@ENDNODE
@NODE Aligner.AmiCAD "Script Align.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Align.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.04, Aligner.AmiCAD)
	It's used to align the selected elements. It's better
	to select some objects of the same type to make the script to
	work correctly.
	A requester makes possible to choose hew is done the operation :
	    - on top
	    - on bottom
	    - on the left side
	    - on the right side

	You can cancel the action of this script using the @{"Undo menu" LINK Undo}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE BoîteArrondie.AmiCAD "Script RoundedBox.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}RoundedBox.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.04, BoîteArrondie.AmiCAD)
	This script is used to draw a box with rounded corners, using arcs.
	You have to draw the box using the left mouse button after you have
	called the script. If you don't want to use the grid, you must have
	unselected the @{"Drawing/Snap on grid" LINK "Snap on grid"} menu BEFORE calling
	the script.
	Then a requester ask you to enter a value to define the radius of the arcs
	used to draw the corners of the box, don't enter too big values or you'll
	get some strange results... If you enter a negative value an error will
	occur.

	To change the width of the box, double clic on a side of the box, move
	the cursor defining the width of the line, mark the Extend cell of the
	line type, then fix the application gadget using "All selected objects"
	and click on OK to validate the requester.

	You can cancel the action of this script using the @{"Undo menu" LINK Undo}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE CadrerTexte.AmiCAD "Script TextFrame.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}TextFrame.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.07, CadrerTexte.AmiCAD)
	This script is used to create a box around one or several texts.
	The texts must be selected begore calling the script.

	The component @{"references" LINK Reference} or @{"values" LINK Value} are not used.

	If the script succeed, the box around the texts, and the texts
	are grouped in a same @{"groupe" LINK Groupes}.

	You can cancel the action of this script using the @{"Undo menu" LINK Undo}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Centrer.AmiCAD "Script Center.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Center.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.03, Centrer.AmiCAD)
	This script is used to center component references and values.
	You must select the components you want to be centered before
	calling the script.

	You can use the @{"Edition/Undo" LINK Undo} menu to cancel
	the action of the script.
@ENDNODE
@NODE AmiPCB.AmiCAD "Script AmiPCB.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}AmiPCB.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.02)
	This script is used to call AmiPCB while using AmiCAD.
	AmiPCB is launched if no ARexx port is found. If any port
	is found, AmiPCB window is placed to the front of the screen.
	RunAmiPCB.script is used to launch AmiPCB, it expects that
	AmiPCB and AmiCAD drawers are at the same place.

	Nota : AmiCAD must have been launched from its own drawer
	(it can be a problem when using programs like AmiDisk or
	AmiDock, ToolManager...) or the script will not be found.
@ENDNODE
@NODE AmiPlot.AmiCAD "Script AmiPlot.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}AmiPlot.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.00)
	This script is used to display the results of a simulation done with
	Spice (it uses the rawfile created by Spice).
	The program used is @{"AmiPlot" LINK AmiPlot}, normally installed in the
	AmiCAD drawer, but if the simulation is done to compute the operating
	point, the results will be displayed in an AmiCAD requester.
@ENDNODE
@NODE CAD2PCB.AmiCAD "Script CAD2PCB.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}CAD2PCB.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.03)
	This script is used to create a netlist for AmiPCB.
	Warning : you must have compiled the netlist before
	calling this script (see @{"CreateNets" LINK CreateNets} or @{"NewCreateNets" LINK NewCreateNets} script).
	The components on the sheet must have their footprint field
	defined. If some of the footprints are missing, the script will
	help you to add them.

	When all is done, you must choose a file to save the netlist. You can
	save the file in the RAM: disk (it's a little file, and you don't have
	to keep it after it has been imported in AmiPCB).
	This file is different from the Spice netlists, it can only be used
	by AmiPCB to create a board with the components present on the AmiCAD
	page, using the nets defined on it.
	If you change something on the sheet after AmiPCB had imported the
	file, you can create the netlist again with AmiCAD, and import it
	again with AmiPCB (always using the ImportAmiCADNetlist script), without
	deleting the existing drawing (nets will be redefined).

	All components of the Symboles_Spice library are ignored as they are
	normally used for simulation only.

	@{b}Nota :@{ub} this script uses the rexxdossupport.library, available
	on Aminet (version 3.5).
@ENDNODE
@NODE CheckNoPCB.AmiCAD "Script CheckNoPCB.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}CheckNoPCB.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.01)
	This script is used to found the components with no linked footprint.
	When the script is called, all these components are marked. You can
	edit them to define the missing footprints.

	All components of the Symboles_Spice library are ignored as they are
	normally used for simulation only.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Calc.AmiCAD "Script Calc.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Calc.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.02)
	This script is used to do a calculation (maybe complexe) and to
	write the result on the current page.
	You must have the rexxmathlib.library installed on your system
	to use this script.
	When the script is launched, a requester is opened to enter the
	formula to evaluate.
	Next functions are available : abs acos acosh asin asinh atan atanh
	ceil cos cosh cot cotan csc exp fabs fact floor int ln log10 nint
	pow(x,y) sec sin sinh sqrt tan tanh. Of course you can also use the
	classic operators like +-*/ and ().
	Angles are in radians.

	Example :
	  To compute the value of PI:
	    asin(1)*2
@ENDNODE
@NODE Caractčre.AmiCAD "Script WriteChar.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}WriteChar.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.03, Caractčre.AmiCAD)
	This script is used to write a @{"special char" LINK CHR} from the
	AmiCAD font. These chars are used to display some components parts
	as the amplifier symbol (a triangle).
	A requester is opened with the name of each char, clicking on one
	of them place the corresponding symbol under the cursor, so you
	can place it anywhere.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Cartouche.AmiCAD "Script Cartouche.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Cartouche.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.10)
	This script is used to draw a cartouche on the current page
	(a cartridge case). The drawing include a rectangle around the
	whole page, and six little rectangles in a corner of the page,
	with a title, a document number, the revision number, the
	date... The main title and the society name must be entered in
	a requester, then the dimensions of the drawing will be set
	according the length of the strings.
	The date is set using the rexxlocaldates.library.
	Since version 1.09 you can call the script using an argument :
	if you are always using the same society name you give it
	there, so you have not to enter it each time. The 13x6 toolbar
	includes an icon for this script, just edit the command to
	get something like this (first line, column nine) :
	    CALL("Cartouche","BIDON Society S.A.")

	You can cancel the action of this script using the @{"Undo menu" LINK Undo}
	and you can also modify the included strings of the drawing (just
	double clic on the texts).
@ENDNODE
@NODE ChargeRC.AmiCAD "Script ChargeRC.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}ChargeRC.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.02)
	This script is used to draw the charge and discharge voltages for a
	resistance and condensator circuit.
	You must draw and select a box before calling the script. The plot
	will be done in it. Let some free place to the left and under the
	box to display the legend.

	You can cancel the action of this script using the @{"Undo menu" LINK Undo}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ChercherTexte.AmiCAD "Script ChercherTexte.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}ChercherTexte.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.03)
	This script is used to find a text on the current page. Searching is
	done on texts, references, values but not on labels and connectors.
	For references and values you can use wildcards (*[]()... ) to specify
	the searched string (R* would find all resistances).
	For the texts, the search is case sensitive.
	If a text is selected while the script is called all other texts with
	the same string will be selected.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ChoixFormat.AmiCAD "Script ChoixFormat.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}ChoixFormat.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.02)
	This script is used to define the dimensions of the current page.
	It is possible to select an A4 page (vertical or horizontal) for
	two aspect ratios.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ChoixSignaux.AmiCAD "Script ChoixSignaux.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}ChoixSignaux.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.02)
	This script is an old script, it has not been updated for the
	the new Symboles_Spice library. So it's unusable for the moment.

	Now if you want Spice to keep the results of a simulation, you have
	to place a component of this Symboles_Spice library (VOLTAGE_PROBE
	or INTENSITY_PROBE) on the document.
	You can add an OSCILLOSCOPE to display only some signals (see examples).
@ENDNODE
@NODE ControlNets.AmiCAD "Script ControlNets.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}ControlNets.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.01)
	This script is used to check and display the netlist created
	for simulation. You must have previously compiled this netlist
	(see @{"NewCreateNets" LINK NewCreateNets.AmiCAD} script).
	When called, the script opens a requester for each line of the
	netlist, with the content of the line, and the component is
	selected on the document (Spice netlist include a line for each
	component of the circuit).
@ENDNODE
@NODE Conv2META.AmiCAD "Script Conv2META.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Conv2META.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.04)
	This script is using the AmiCAD2META program to convert the
	AmiCAD files to some other formats. @{"AmiCAD2META" LINK AmiCAD2META} has not been
	updated since 2001, so the last data included in the new
	documents are not supported, it only handles the page files.

	You must have installed @{b}MetaView@{ub} to be able to use this script.
	You must edit the script to make it able to work on your system.
	(see line 11).

	The next formats are availables :
	    AMF (Amiga MetaFile)
	    WMF (Windows MetaFile)
	    DR2D (Drawing 2D)
	    CGM (ComputerGraphicMetafile)
	    GEM
	    EPS (Encapsulated PostScript)
	    AI (Adobe Illustrator)
	    HPGL (Hewlett-Packard Graphics Language)
	    ILBM (InterLeaved BitMap)
	    JMF (Java MetaFile)
	    FIG
	    META (MetaView)
	I have not often used this program because I found
	that the results are not very good.
@ENDNODE
@NODE CreateNets.AmiCAD "Script CreateNets.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}CreateNets.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.04)
	This script is used to compile the netlist of the current page.
	It's an old script, a newer script, faster, is now used to do
	this job (@{"NewCreateNets" LINK NewCreateNets.AmiCAD}).
@ENDNODE
@NODE Date.AmiCAD "Script Date.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Date.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.01)
	This script is used to write the current date under the cursor.
	Then you can place it whenever you want (a text will be created).
	This script is using the rexxlocaldates.library, it must be
	installed on your system.
@ENDNODE
@NODE DefSignal.AmiCAD "Script DefSignal.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}DefSignal.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.00)
	This script is used to define a voltage source used in
	a simulation. It's using the AWNPipe handler written by
	William H. M. Parker, available on Aminet.
	You can define the next sources types :
	    - DC voltage
	    - Sinusoidal (SIN)
	    - Pulsed (PULSE)
	    - Exponential (EXP)
	    - Piece-Wise-Linear (PWL)
	    - Single-Frequency FM (SFFM)
	You can select the source to define before calling the
	script, or choose it after, or define a anew source.

	You can cancel the action of this script using the @{"Undo menu" LINK Undo}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE EditComponents.AmiCAD "Script EditComponents.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}EditComponents.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.02)
	This can be used to edit all the components of a page.
	It's using AWNPipe to create a requester with a list of all
	the components, with their references, values, etc...
	But this script is not yet finished, it's not possible
	to modify something for the moment (but a double clic
	on the name of a component open the editor window).
	You can call the script while only some components are
	selected, so only these objects will be present in the
	requester. The script can also be called with the ALL
	argument (all components will be edited).
@ENDNODE
@NODE EditConnect.AmiCAD "Scipt EditConnect.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}EditConnect.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.01)
	This script is used to edit a connector of the Symboles_AmiCAD
	library . It's using AWNPipe to create a requester with the
	connector name, the name of the signal, the pin number and
	the connector type (Input or output).
	You can modify each data, the connector will be choosen
	between the existing models (the width will correspond to
	the length of the signal name).
	The connectors edited with this script can be placed using
	the @{"PutConnect" LINK PutConnect.AmiCAD} script.

	You can cancel the action of this script using the @{"Undo menu" LINK Undo}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE EditScript.AmiCAD "Script EditScript.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}EditScript.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.05)
	This script is used to run a text editor to edit an AmiCAD
	script. It is written for my text editor Amitex, but it can
	be adapted for another program, if it has an Arexx port.
	AmiTex has to be installed in the SYS:Utilities/AmiTex
	drawer to make the script working.

	The rexxsupport.library must be installed to use this script.

	Nota : you can edit some scripts linked to the @{"Scripts" LINK Scripts} menu
	selecting the menu while pressing the Ctrl key.
	Doing this will call this script with the name of the
	selected menu as an argument (the script will be loaded
	directly in the text editor window).
	If the script is called without any argument, an asl
	requester is opened to select the script to edit.
@ENDNODE
@NODE EditString.AmiCAD "Script EditString.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}EditString.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.03)
	This script is used to modify the string linked to an object
	(component, text, connector, label...) without opening the
	editor requester.
	The object must be selected before calling the script. If
	it's a component, the reference and the value are edited.

	You can cancel the action of this script using the @{"Undo menu" LINK Undo}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE FindPort.AmiCAD "Script FindPort.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}FindPort.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.00)
	This script is used to know if an ARexx port is available.
	Each AmiCAD document has its own ARexx port called
	AmiCAD.0, AmiCAD.1, etc... But AmiCAD.0 is perhaps closed
	while AmiCAD.1 is already present at a given moment.
	So this script is used to know if an AmiCAD port is
	useable at any moment. It returns the number of the
	first port that is founded (AmiCAD.5 returns 5).
	If no port is found (AmiCAD is not running) an empty
	string is returned.

	Nota : if an argument is given to the script another
	port name can be searched. Calling the script with
	the AmiTex argument will do a search for the AmiPCB.0,
	AmiPCB.1 ports (and next).

	Be carefull : AmiCAD is not equivalent to Amicad, you
	must take care of the case for each letter when you
	specify a port name.
@ENDNODE
@NODE FixQuotes.AmiCAD "Script FixQuotes.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}FixQuotes.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.00)
	This script is used to double " that are present in a string.
	Some scripts are using it when necessary, for some functions.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Grille.AmiCAD "Script Grid.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Grid.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.10, Grille.AmiCAD)
	This script is used to draw a grid with linear or log horizontal
	and vertical axes.
	You can call the script in the two next ways :
	    - either you draw a box in which the grid will be drawned.
	    Tou then select this box and call the script
	    - either you call directly the script and draw the box using
	    the left mouse button.
	You have to enter how many decades you want to draw in the grid,
	and how you want to fill it (linear, log...)
	When the script is ended the new grid is selected, you can then
	cut it, delete it, move it...

	You can cancel the action of this script using the @{"Undo menu" LINK Undo}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE GuideSpice.AmiCAD "Script GuideSpice.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}GuideSpice.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.00)
	This script is used to launch MultiView to display the Spice
	guide.
	This guide must be located in /Spice/SpiceGuide/Spice3f4.guide
	(The Spice drawer must be located in the same place than the
	AmiCAD one).
@ENDNODE
@NODE ImportClip1.0.AmiCAD "Script ImportClip1.0.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}ImportClip1.0.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.04)
	This script is used to load some old clips created with AmiCAD
	versions older than 2.00 (1999). It's not really usefull now...
@ENDNODE
@NODE ImportFile1.0.AmiCAD "Script ImportFile1.0.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}ImportFile1.0.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.09)
	This script is used to load some old files created with AmiCAD
	versions older than 2.00 (1999). It's not really usefull now...
@ENDNODE
@NODE ImportTexte.AmiCAD "Script ImportText.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}ImportText.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.06, ImportTexte.AmiCAD)
	This script is used to import a text in a rectangular zone.
	You can used two ways to call this script :
	    - either you draw a box in which the text will fit, you
	    select this box, and call the script
	    - either you can the script and you'll have to draw the
	    box using the left mouse button.
	When the zone is defined you have to choose the text file
	to place in this box using an asl requester.
	If the whole text doesn't fit in the box a message is displayed
	at the end of the script execution.
	The new text is selected, so you can cut it, delete it or
	move it...

	You can cancel the action of this script using the @{"Undo menu" LINK Undo}.

	Nota : the script doesn't handle the current scale and the text
	rotation mode. The used scale is always 100, in the normal
	direction (no rotation).
@ENDNODE
@NODE InitObjets.AmiCAD "Script InitObjets.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}InitObjets.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.02)
	This script is used to define some AmiCAD variables, these
	variables are filled with the different types of AmiCAD objects.

	This script is normaly called at the beginning of a script.

	Version 1.01 checks the locale to know what's the current language.
	The returned value is 1 if french is used, 0 else. For the moment
	no other locale is handled, but it is possible to add other
	locales (by example, 2 could be used for german).

	You can call this script like in the next examples :
	 1- 'INITOBJECTS=0:CALL("InitObjets.AmiCAD")'
	    initobjects=0
	    do while initobjects=0
		'INITOBJECTS'
		initobjects=result
	    end

	 2- 'CADPATH'                       /* The two first lines can be deleted */
	    r=pragma(D,result)              /* if AmiCAD is launched from its */
	    call 'ARexx/InitObjets.AmiCAD'  /* drawer (normal case) */

	 3- fr='ARexx/InitObjets.AmiCAD'()
	 In this last example the fr variable is 1 if the current
	 locale is french, else it's set to 0.

    Next values are defined (see also @{"TYPE" LINK TYPE} function):
	COMPOSANT	1
	FIL		2
	ARC		3
	TEXTE		4
	REFERENCE	5
	VALEUR		6
	JONCTION	7
	POINTILLES	8
	BUS		9
	ELLIPSE 	10
	CERCLE		10
	INPUT		11
	OUTPUT		12
	LIGNE_DOUBLE	15
	TRAIT		21
	BOITE		22
	JONCTION_CARREE 23
	BOITE_PLEINE	24
	TRIANGLE	26
	TRIANGLE_PLEIN	27
	LABEL		28
@ENDNODE
@NODE Karnaugh.AmiCAD "Script Karnaugh.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Karnaugh.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.03)
	This script is used to create a Karnaugh array. You have to
	enter the inputs number, their names, the outputs number
	and their names.

	When the script is ended, the array is selected, you can
	cut it, or move it, as you like.

	You can cancel the action of this script using the @{"Undo menu" LINK Undo}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE LinkNets.AmiCAD "Script LinkNets.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}LinkNets.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.01)
	This script is used to call next scripts :
	    - @{"NewCreateNets" LINK NewCreateNets.AmiCAD} (netlist creation)
	    - @{"  Nets2File  " LINK Nets2File.AmiCAD} (saving the netlist to disk)
	    - @{" Simulation  " LINK Simulation.AmiCAD} (running Spice)

	See also : @{"Simulate" LINK Simulate.AmiCAD} script.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Majuscules.AmiCAD "Script UPPERCASE.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}UPPERCASE.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.06, Majuscules.AmiCAD)
	This script is used to convert a text to upper case.
	You must select the text(s) to convert before calling
	the script. You can also select component references,
	values, labels, connectors...

	You can cancel the action of this script using the @{"Undo menu" LINK Undo}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE MapKey.AmiCAD "Script MapKey.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}MapKey.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.03)
	This script is used to define the programming coupled to a key
	sequence. Enter the key sequence (Ex: alt-a, f1, shift-F11), then
	enter or modify the command using the next requester (you can
	use the left button to select one of the available functions).
@ENDNODE
@NODE MarkPins.AmiCAD "Script MarkPins.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}MarkPins.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.01)
	This script is used to display the nodes numbers associated to
	components. These numbers define the order of the nets that are
	listed in a Spice netlist.
	The script show these numbers, for the first selected component.
	The node numbers are displayed using some texts, placed near the
	pins. They can be deleted using the @{"Undo menu" LINK Undo}.
	To do a simulation, the nodes number have to be the same than in
	the Spice model used for simulation. If they are not equal, you
	can use the Nodes field of the components to change them.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Nets2File.AmiCAD "Script Nets2File.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Nets2File.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.03)
	This script is used to save the netlist on disk. You must have
	used the @{"NewCreateNets" LINK NewCreateNets.AmiCAD}) script before.
	When the netlist has been saved on disk, you can use the @{"Simulation" LINK Simulation.AmiCAD}
	script to make the simulation.

	Voltage and intensity probes are checked to define the signals
	that will be saved during the simulation (this components are
	found in the Symboles_Spice library).
@ENDNODE
@NODE NewCreateNets.AmiCAD "Script NewCreateNets.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}NewCreateNets.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 2.02)
	This script is used to create a netlist that will be used to
	do an analog simulation using Spice.
	It scans the current page of the sheet to find the different
	nets, and it keeps the results in some arrays linked to the
	sheet.
	Warning : if you modify the sheet, you have to call again
	this script to update the data of the netlist.

	You must use the @{"Nets2File" LINK Nets2File.AmiCAD} script to save this
	netlist on disk, to be able to run the simulation.

	An older script, slower because not using the last net menu,
	(@{"CreateNets" LINK CreateNets.AmiCAD}), is already present, but not supported.
@ENDNODE
@NODE NewScript.AmiCAD "Script NewScript.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}NewScript.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.06)
	This script is used to create new scripts. It is written
	to use my own text editor (Amitex), but it can be easily
	adapted for any other text editor, with an Arexx port.
	When calling the script, Amitex is loaded, and a script
	with a minimal set of lines is loaded in the window.
	You have to enter the name of the new script, then this
	name is written at the good place in the script, to
	display error messages, and the script is renamed to suit
	the given filename.
@ENDNODE
@NODE NewWindow.AmiCAD ScriptNewWindow.AmiCAD
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}NewWindow.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.01)
	This script is used to create a new document. The script
	can be called with the name of the new document as an
	argument. The returned value is the AmiCAD port number (from
	0 to 99) if the function has succeeded, -1 else.

    @{i}Example :@{ui}
	    call 'NewWindow.AmiCAD' filename
	    code = result
	    if code>=0 then do
		new_port = 'AmiCAD.'||code
		address VALUE new_port
		... working with the new document ...
	    end
	    else 'MESSAGE("Error opening new document")'
@ENDNODE
@NODE Nomenclature.AmiCAD "Script Nomenclature.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Nomenclature.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.01)
	This script is used to set the component list of the current
	sheet. You can save this list on disk, so it will be possible
	to edit it with a text editor.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PurgeTempFiles.AmiCAD "Script PurgeTempFiles.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}PurgeTempFiles.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.00)
	This script is used to delete temporary files created
	during simulations. Each time a simulation is created
	using the @{"Simulate" LINK Simulate.AmiCAD} script, a .cir file and a data file
	are saved in RAM:. Most of the time, the first file is
	not very important, but the second one can be very large.
	So it can be usefull to delete all these files from time
	to time, specially when you are light in memory.

	Warnin: calling this script gives an error if none of the
	simulation file has been created before.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PutConnect.AmiCAD "Script PutConnect.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}PutConnect.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.01)
	This script is used to place a connector on the current sheet.
	It uses AWNPipe to create a requester with the connector name,
	the signal name, the pin number and the connector type (Input
	or Output).
	It's used to select a connector of the Symboles_AmiCAD library.
	These connectors have 7 different models, with different
	dimensions, than can handle different name length. The script
	choose the best model according to the length name. Pin numbers
	can be choosen between 1 and 250. It you enter 0 as pin number,
	this number will be hidden.
	Such connectors can be edited using the @{"EditConnect" LINK EditConnect.AmiCAD} script.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ReadPCBClip.AmiCAD "Script ReadPCBClip.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}ReadPCBClip.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.01)
	This script is used to read a clip file of AmiPCB, in fact a
	PCB footprint.
	The footprint is drawned at the top left corner of the current
	sheet. It's selected, so you can copy it, cut it or move it.
	This script let you see the footprints linked to components
	without running AmiPCB. So you can know where are located the
	different pins.

	You can cancel the action of this script using the @{"Undo menu" LINK Undo}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Recopier.AmiCAD "Script Duplicate.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Duplicate.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.07, Recopier.AmiCAD)
	This script is used to place some identical elements on a sheet.
	To place ten resistances, referenced R1 to R10, place the first
	resistance, attribute its reference (R1 or anything else), place
	some wires if you want, then select it and call the script.
	Then choose the direction of the copy (to the right, to the
	left...), select the number of copies to do, the spacing beetween
	the different elements and look at the result.
	New references are set according to the already present components.

	You can cancel the action of this script using the @{"Undo menu" LINK Undo}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Redimensionner.AmiCAD "Script Redimensionner.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Redimensionner.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.00)
	This script is used to crop the current sheet, if it's too large.
	Just click on the right side, then on the bottom side, and the
	sheet will be changed.
	Warning : it's impossible to undo this operation, so be carefull...
	If some components are out of the keeped zone, they will be
	lost for ever.

	You can cancel the script using the right mouse button, before
	using the left mouse button. You can use the proportional gadgets
	to choose the limits of the keeped zone.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Référencer.AmiCAD "Script AddRefs.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}AddRefs.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.11, Référencer.AmiCAD)
	This script is used to add some references to components that
	have not been set.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SauverAuto.AmiCAD "Script AutoSauve.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}AutoSauve.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 2.04, SauverAuto.AmiCAD)
	This script is used to execute an automatic saving each
	two minutes (if the sheet content has been modified).
	To cancel this operation, call this script again.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Save2GIF.AmiCAD "Script Save2GIF.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Save2GIF.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.04)
	This script is used to save the current sheet in an image
	using the GIF format. It uses the @{"SAVEIFF" LINK SAVEIFF} command, then
	the tapgif command (available on Aminet).
@ENDNODE
@NODE SaveNets.AmiCAD "Script SaveNets.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}SaveNets.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.10)
	This script is used to create and save a netlist, then it can
	be simulated. It's an old script.
	Using @{"NewCreateNets" LINK NewCreateNets.AmiCAD} and"Nets2File" LINK Nets2File.AmiCAD} is better.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SearchLib.AmiCAD "Script SearchLib.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}SearchLib.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.04)
	This script is used to search a component in the libraries.
	You can enter a component name using wildcards (Ex: 74LS14*).
	The script uses the SearchLib program, that have to be
	located in the AmiCAD drawer. Results are displayed in
	a Shell window.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SelectNet.AmiCAD "Script SelectNet.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}SelectNet.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.09)
	This script is used to display a net. You can select a wire
	before calling the script before calling the script or after.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SelectParts.AmiCAD "Script SelectParts.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}SelectParts.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.07)
	This script is used to select all the components of a
	given type. You can select the type to select before
	calling the script, or choose it in a requester after
	calling the script.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SetMasks.AmiCAD "Script SetMasks.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}SetMasks.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.02)
	This script is used to set footprints to the selected
	components. If several components have no footprint they
	will be set with the same footprint if they are identical.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ShowModel.AmiCAD "Script ShowModel.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}ShowModel.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.01)
	This script is used  to call Amitex to display the
	associated model of a component.
	This component must be selected before calling the
	script.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ShowNoPCBMask.AmiCAD "Script ShowNoPCBMask.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}ShowNoPCBMask.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.02)
	This script is used to select the components without an
	associated footprint.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ShowPCBMasks.AmiCAD "Script ShowPCBMasks.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}ShowPCBMasks.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.00)
	This script is used to select the components with an
	associated footprint.
@ENDNODE
@TOC ARexxScripts
@NODE Simulate.AmiCAD "Script Simulate.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Simulate.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.00)
	This script is used to link all the scripts doing a complete
	simulation, but without @{"checking" LINK TestNets.AmiCAD} the sheet for errors.
	Next scripts are called :
	    - @{"NewCreateNets" LINK NewCreateNets.AmiCAD} (Netlist creation)
	    - @{"  Nets2File  " LINK Nets2File.AmiCAD} (Saving the netlist in RAM:)
	    - @{"  Simulation " LINK Simulation.AmiCAD} (Running Spice)
	    - @{"   AmiPlot   " LINK AmiPlot.AmiCAD} (Displaying results)
@ENDNODE
@NODE Simulation.AmiCAD "Script Simulation.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Simulation.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.06)
	This script is used to launch a simulation using Spice.
	Spice drawer must have been installed in the same drawer
	than AmiCAD, or you have to modify the script.
	The executable have to be Spice3f5PPC, located in Spice/bin.
	SpicePPC is available on OS4 depot.

	If the simulation is correctly launched, a Shell window
	is opened (titled Spice), Spice displays some error messages
	and warnings in it. Read carefully the messages to locate
	the problems.
	This window must be closed with the mouse at the end of
	the simulation.

	The results of the simulation are saved in a rawfile located
	in RAM:. If the simulated netlist is called test.cir, the
	rawfile will be called RAM:test_data.

	If you want Spice to keep the results of a simulation, you have
	to place a component of the Symboles_Spice library (VOLTAGE_PROBE
	or INTENSITY_PROBE) on the document.
	You can add an OSCILLOSCOPE to display only some signals (see
	examples).
@ENDNODE
@NODE SimulUtils.AmiCAD "Script SimulUtils.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}SimulUtils.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.00)
	This script opens a requester with some buttons relative
	to simulation scripts. If you select a button, the related
	script will be launched.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Souligner.AmiCAD "Script UnderLine.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}UnderLine.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.03, Souligner.AmiCAD)
	This script is used to underline a text. You can select the
	text(s) to underline before calling the script, or do it after.
	Component values and references can also be underlined.

	You can cancel the action of this script using the @{"Undo menu" LINK Undo}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE TableVérité.AmiCAD "Script TruthTable.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}TruthTable.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.02, TableVérité.AmiCAD)
	This script is used to draw a truth table for the specified number
	of inputs and outputs. A the end of the script, the truth table is
	selected (it's always located at the top left side of the sheet).
	You can copy it, move it or resize it... It's even possible to
	make the program filling it, using NOT, OR, AND, NAND and XOR
	functions (2 inputs each for the last four).
	Example : vous specify that your table have 2 inputs, called I1
	and I2, 2 outputs called Q1 and Q2. You can ask the program to
	fill the table with the next equations :
	    AND(I1,NOT(I2)) for Q1 and OR(I1,I2) for Q2.

	You can cancel the action of this script using the @{"Undo menu" LINK Undo}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE TestNets.AmiCAD "Script TestNets.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}TestNets.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.08)
	This script can be used before a simulation, to find the
	common errors on the sheet. You can choose to check only
	component references, values, connections, nets, redundancies
	or make all of this.
@ENDNODE
@NODE TirerTraits.AmiCAD "Script DragLines.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}DragLines.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.06, TirerTraits.AmiCAD)
	This script can be used to align the limits of a lines
	set. The lines must be selected before calling the script.
	doivent ętre sélectionnées avant l'appel du script.
	A request is used to select the extremity of the line
	to move. Then just click on the column or on the line
	where this extremity will be moved.

	You can cancel the action of this script using the @{"Undo menu" LINK Undo}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Tourner.AmiCAD "Script Rotate.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Rotate.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.02, Tourner.AmiCAD)
	This script is used to rotate a component without rotating
	its reference and its value, if any of them exist.
	You can select the component(s) to rotate before calling
	the script or do it after.

	You can cancel the action of this script using the @{"Undo menu" LINK Undo}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE TracerSpice.AmiCAD "Script TraceSpice.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}TraceSpice.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.10, TracerSpice.AmiCAD)
	This script is used to read the results of a simulation
	and to display them in an AmiCAD window. It uses the
	rawfiles produced by Spice.
	The @{"AmiPlot" LINK AmiPlot.AmiCAD} script using the @{"AmiPlot" LINK AmiPlot} program can
	replace this script. However it's always used to display
	the results of an OP analysis ((operating point).
@ENDNODE
@NODE TypeAnalyse.AmiCAD "Script Analyse.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Analyse.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 2.05, TypeAnalyse.AmiCAD)
	This script can help you to define the needed parameters
	to simulate a circuit, for a given analysis.
	The analysis is placed on the sheet using a symbol of the
	Symboles_Spice library.
	For the moment you can use the next symbols :
	    - OP ANALYSIS (operating point analysis)
	    - TRANSIENT ANALYSIS
	    - AC SWEEP ANALYSIS
	    - NOISE ANALYSIS
	    - DC SWEEP ANALYSIS
	    - DISTORTION ANALYSIS
	When necessary a request using AWNPipe is opened to define the
	parameters of the requested analysis. If you click on OK, the
	selected component is placed on the sheet. Parameters are linked
	to the component using its value.

	You have to @{"save the netlist" LINK Nets2File.AmiCAD} to make it working.
@ENDNODE
@NODE VisuNet.AmiCAD "Script VisuNet.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}VisuNet.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.00)
	This script displays a selected net. You must have compiled
	the netlist before launching the script (see @{"NewCreateNets" LINK NewCreateNets.AmiCAD}).
	The net have to be selected in a listview, with all
	the net names in it, then it's selected on the sheet.

	Nota : if you modify the sheet, you have to compile again
	the netlist.
@ENDNODE
@NODE VisuNetlist.AmiCAD "Script DisplayNetList.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}DisplayNetList.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.01, VisuNetlist.AmiCAD)
	This script load a netlist (saved on disk) in a text editor.
	It's written for my text editor, Amitex, but it can be easily
	changed for any other text editor.
@ENDNODE
@NODE VisuNets.AmiCAD "Script VisuNets.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}VisuNets.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.01)
	This script can display the nets of a sheet. You must have compiled
	the netlist before launching the script (see @{"NewCreateNets" LINK NewCreateNets.AmiCAD}).
	The nets are displayed one by one, and their name is displayed
	in a requester, where you can choose to continue (display next
	net) or cancel the operation.

	Nota : if you modify the sheet, you have to compile again
	the netlist.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Zoom.AmiCAD "Script Zoom.AmiCAD"
@TOC ARexxScripts

    @{b}Zoom.AmiCAD@{ub} (Version 1.03)
	This script modify the scale of a group of objects.
	You must select these objects before calling the script.
	You have to enter the horizontal and vertical scale factors
	to transform these objects.
	A value of 100 doesn't change anything, a greater value
	expand the size, a smaller value reduce the size.

	You can cancel the action of this script using the @{"Undo menu" LINK Undo}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ToolBars "Barres d'outils"
@TOC MAIN

    Toolbars can be easily created drawing an image (loaded by
    the datatypes). The image is divided into X columns by Y
    lines (each icon have the same size). The image must be
    associated to an .info file, where the tooltypes define the
    number of icons and the associated @{"commands" LINK "Ecriture commandes"},
    these commands can use any ARexx @{"functions" LINK Fonctions}.

    To @{B}create a new toolbar@{UB}, create an image with a
    program like PPaint, TVPaint or any other one. Save this image
    as a brush, keeping one pixel on the borders (all the icons
    must have the same dimensions). Then you can edit the
    image tooltypes, adding the COLUMNS and LINES tooltypes
    as a minimum. The commands can then be edited using
    AmiCAD : load the toolbar, select it using the left mouse
    button (click on the title bar), then click on any icon with
    the @{b}right mouse@{ub} button.
    A requester is opened, choose a button to select the action
    you want to do (edit, or save commands). To test the command
    then click on the icon using the left mouse button.

    Don't remember @{b}to save@{ub} the result when all is
    working like you want.

    @{b}Warning:@{ub} if you are using a paint program to edit the image,
    be carefull : some of these programs are clearing all the
    tooltypes when saving your work, if so, work on a copy of
    the image.

    Description of some toolbars
	@{"AmiCAD Project   " LINK ProjectBar}
	@{"Barre 13x6       " LINK Barre13x6}
	@{"AmiCAD Drawing   " LINK DrawingBar}
	@{"AmiCAD Edition   " LINK EditionBar}
	@{"AmiCAD Simulation" LINK SimulationBar}

    See also : @{"TOOLBAR" LINK TOOLBAR} function.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ProjectBar "AmiCAD Project toolbar"
@TOC ToolBars

    This toolbar have 2 lines by 11 columns (22 icons).
    First line (from left to right) :
	- Normal scale (Zoom 100%)                                  IF(ZOOM(0)<>100,ZOOM(100),0)
	- Get position and dimensions of the current window	    _ZOOM_=ZOOM(0):_WINWIDTH_=MESURE(2):_WINHEIGHT_=MESURE(3):_XWIN_=MESURE(0):_YWIN_=MESURE(1)
	- Restaure position and dimensions of the current window    IF(_ZOOM_>10,ZOOM(_ZOOM_):WINDOW(_XWIN_,_YWIN_,_WINWIDTH_,_WINHEIGHT_),IF(MESURE(2)==0,WINDOW(-1,-1,-1,-1),MESSAGE("Dimensions fenętre non sauvées")))
	- Full height window					    MENU("4-")
	- Full width window					    MENU("0-")
	- Zoom on a box area					    MENU("2-")
	- Zoom in						    MENU("6-")
	- Zoom out						    MENU("9-")
	- Redraw current window content 			    MENU("Redraw")
	- Select a toolbar to load				    _BAR_=REQFILE("Chargement barre","ToolBars",""):IF(_BAR_<>"",IF(LOADBAR(_BAR_),MESSAGE("Chargement barre impossible"),""),0)
	- Load the @{"AmiCAD drawing" LINK DrawingBar} toolbar                           LOADBAR("ToolBars/AmiCAD Drawing")
    Second line :
	- Close the current window				    IF((MODIF==0) | (OBJECTS==0),CLOSE(-1),IF(REQUEST("ATTENTION! Le document"+CHR(10)+"a été modifié !"+CHR(10)+"Voulez-vous quand-męme le fermer ?")==1,CLOSE(0),0))
	- Load a document from disk				    MENU("Load")
	- Save the document on disk				    MENU("Save")
	- Select a recent file (to load)                            MENU("Open recent")
	- Printing page 					    MENU("Print")
	- Informations						    MENU("Info")
	- Open a new document					    NEWSHEET
	- Iconify the window					    IF(MESURE(2)>0,MENU("Iconify"),ZOOM(ZOOM(-1)))
	- Hide the window (or open it again)                        IF(MESURE(2)<>0,MENU("Hide"),ZOOM(ZOOM(-1)))
	- Load the @{"AmiCAD Simulation" LINK SimulationBar} toolbar                      LOADBAR("Toolbars/AmiCAD Simulation")
	- Load the @{"AmiCAD Edition" LINK SimulationBar} toolbar                       LOADBAR("Toolbars/AmiCAD Edition")
@ENDNODE
@NODE Barre13x6 "Barre 13x6 toolbar"
@TOC ToolBars

    This toolbar have 6 lines by 13 columns (78 icons).
    First line (from left to right) :
	- Place wires		    UNMARK(-1):CURSMODE(2):DRAWMODE(1)
		Initialization	    (CURSMODE(-1)==2)&(DRAWMODE(1000)==1)
	- Small grid		    SETGRID(5)
		Initialization	    IF(SETGRID(0)==5,1,0)
	- Place text		    UNMARK(-1):MENU("Place text")
		Initialization	    CURSMODE(-1)==4
	- Select component	    UNMARK(-1):CURSMODE(-1):MENU("Choose component")
	- Place last component	    UNMARK(-1):CURSMODE(1):DRAWMODE(1)
		Initialisation	    CURSMODE(-1)==1
	- Alternate symbol	    MENU("Alternate")
	- Alternate pin numbers     IF(FIRSTSEL,O=FIRSTSEL:WHILE(O,SETPINS(O,IF(SETPINS(O,-1),0,1)),O=NEXTSEL(O)),SETPINS(0,IF(SETPINS(0,-1),0,1)))
	- Move to left		    IF(FIRSTSEL,IF(SNAPGRID(2),P__=SETGRID(0),P__=1):SAVEALL:MOVE(0,-P__,0),MESSAGE("Aucune sélection en cours"))
	- Move to top		    IF(FIRSTSEL,IF(SNAPGRID(2),P__=SETGRID(0),P__=1):SAVEALL:MOVE(0,0,-P__),MESSAGE("Aucune sélection en cours"))
	- Draw cartouche	    CALL("Cartouche","Freeware Softwares")
	- Unzoom		    MENU("9-")
	- Zoom 100%		    IF(ZOOM(0)<>100,ZOOM(100),0)
	- Select a toolbar	    _BAR_=REQFILE("Load toolbar","Barres",""):IF(_BAR_<>"",IF(TOOLBAR(_BAR_),MESSAGE("Chargement barre impossible"),""),0)
    Second line :
	- Place junction mode	    UNMARK(-1):CURSMODE(7)
		Initialization	    CURSMODE(-1)==7
	- Large grid		    SETGRID(10)
		Initialization	    IF(SETGRID(0)==10,1,0)
	- Place input connectors    UNMARK(-1):MENU("Place input")
	- Place resistances	    UNMARK(-1):CURSMODE(-1):PUTPART("Résistance",-1,-1):CURSMODE(1):DRAWMODE(1)
	- Place condensators	    UNMARK(-1):CURSMODE(-1):PUTPART("Condensateur",-1,-1):CURSMODE(1):DRAWMODE(1)
	- Rotation (to right)       MENU("Rotation")
	- Rotation (to left)        IF(FIRSTSEL|(CURSMODE(-2)<2),MENU("Rotat"):MENU("Rotat"):MENU("Rotat"),0)
	- Move to bottom	    IF(FIRSTSEL,IF(SNAPGRID(2),P__=SETGRID(0),P__=1):SAVEALL:MOVE(0,0,P__),MESSAGE("Aucune sélection en cours"))
	- Move to right 	    IF(FIRSTSEL,IF(SNAPGRID(2),P__=SETGRID(0),P__=1):SAVEALL:MOVE(0,P__,0),MESSAGE("Aucune sélection en cours"))
	- Zoom box		    MENU("2-")
	- Zoom in		    MENU("6-")
	- Redraw		    MENU("Redraw")
	- Load Simulation toolbar   TOOLBAR("Barres/SimulationBar")
    Third line :
	- Orthogonal mode ON/OFF    SETORTHO(-1)
		Initialization	    SETORTHO(-2)==0
	- Use grid ON/OFF	    SNAPGRID(-1)
		Initialieation	    SNAPGRID(-2)==0
	- Place output connector    UNMARK(-1):MENU("Place output")
	- Place GROUND2 	    UNMARK(-1):CURSMODE(-1):PUTPART("Masse2",-1,-1):CURSMODE(1):DRAWMODE(1)
	- Place GROUND		    UNMARK(-1):CURSMODE(-1):PUTPART("Masse",-1,-1):CURSMODE(1):DRAWMODE(1)
	- Symmetry		    MENU("Reflection")
	- Pull wires ON/OFF	    MENU("Pull lines")
	- Delete objects	    MENU("Delete")
	- Undo			    MENU("Undo")
	- Iconify window	    MENU("Iconify")
	- Full height window	    MENU("4-")
	- Full width window	    MENU("0-")
	- Load Drawing Toolbar	    LOADBAR("ToolBars/DrawingBar")
    Fourth line :
	- Draw double lines	    UNMARK(-1):CURSMODE(2):DRAWMODE(2)
		Initialization	    (CURSMODE(-2)==2)&(DRAWMODE(1000)==2)
	- Place boxes		    UNMARK(-1):DRAWMODE(1):CURSMODE(22)
		Initialization	    CURSMODE(-1)==22
	- Place powers		    UNMARK(-1):CURSMODE(-1):PUTPART("Alimentation",-1,-1):CURSMODE(1):DRAWMODE(1)
	- Place PNP transistors     UNMARK(-1):CURSMODE(-1):PUTPART("Transistor PNP",-1,-1):CURSMODE(1):DRAWMODE(1)
	- Place NPN transistors     UNMARK(-1):CURSMODE(-1):PUTPART("Transistor NPN",-1,-1):CURSMODE(1):DRAWMODE(1)
	- Add reference & value     CALL("EditString")
	- Clone objects 	    MENU("Clone")
	- Cut			    MENU("Cut")
	- Use clip 1		    CURSMODE(-1):CLIPUNIT(1)
		Initialization	    CLIPUNIT(0)==1
	- Uniconify window	    IF(MESURE(2)<0,ZOOM(ZOOM(-1)),0)
	- New document		    NEWSHEET
	- Informations		    MENU("Info")
	- Reduce window size	    CALL("Redimensionner")
    Fifth line :
	- Draw dashed lines	    UNMARK(-1):CURSMODE(2):DRAWMODE(0)
		Initialisation	    (CURSMODE(-2)==2)&(DRAWMODE(1000)==0)
	- Place triangles	    UNMARK(-1):CURSMODE(26)
		Initialisation	    CURSMODE(-2)==26
	- Surface		    CURSMODE(-1):SETFILL(IF(SETFILL(-1),0,1))
		Initialisation	    SETFILL(-1)
	- Place DELs		    UNMARK(-1):CURSMODE(-1):PUTPART("Diode électroluminescente",-1,-1):CURSMODE(1):DRAWMODE(1)
	- Place sources 	    UNMARK(-1):CURSMODE(-1):PUTPART("Générateur",-1,-1):CURSMODE(1):DRAWMODE(1)
	- Fix on grid		    MENU("Fix on grid")
	- Divide size		    MENU("Divide size")
	- Copy			    MENU("Copy")
	- Use clip 2		    CURSMODE(-1):CLIPUNIT(2)
		Initialization	    CLIPUNIT(0)==2
	- Load document/page	    MENU("Load")
	- Save document 	    MENU("Save")
	- Quit			    IF((MODIF==0) | (OBJECTS==0),CLOSE(-1),IF(REQUEST("WARNING! The document"+CHR(10)+"has been modified !"+CHR(10)+"Do-you want to really close it ?")==1,CLOSE(-1),0))
	- Save AmiPCB netlist	    CALL("CAD2PCB")
    Sixth line :
	- Place special line	    UNMARK(-1):CURSMODE(2):DRAWMODE(-1)
		Initialisation	    (CURSMODE(-2)==2)&(DRAWMODE(1000)<0)
	- Place ellipse/cercle	    UNMARK(-1):CURSMODE(10)
		Initialisation	    CURSMODE(-1)==10
	- Add references	    CALL("Référencer")
	- Place diodes		    UNMARK(-1):CURSMODE(-1):PUTPART("Diode",-1,-1):CURSMODE(1):DRAWMODE(1)
	- Place zeners		    UNMARK(-1):CURSMODE(-1):PUTPART("Diode Zener",-1,-1):CURSMODE(1):DRAWMODE(1)
	- Place to back 	    MENU("To Back")
	- Double size		    MENU("Double size")
	- Paste 		    CURSMODE(-1):MENU("Paste")
	- Use clip 3		    CURSMODE(-1):CLIPUNIT(3)
		Initialization	    CLIPUNIT(0)==3
	- Load clip		    MENU("Load clip")
	- Open recents		    MENU("Open recent")
	- Print 		    MENU("Print")
	- Call AmiPCB		    CALL("AmiPCB")
@ENDNODE
@NODE SimulationBar "AmiCAD Simulation toolbar"
@TOC ToolBars

    This toolbar have 2 lines by 9 columns icons.

    First line (from left to right) :
	- Define source 	    CALL("DefSignal")
	- Define analysis	    CALL("TypeAnalyse")
	- Display simulation model  CALL("ShowModel")
	- View nodes		    CALL("MarkPins")
	- Selection net 	    MENU("Select net")
	- Check circuit 	    CALL("TestNets")
	- View nets		    CALL("VisuNets")
	- Verify netlist	    CALL("ControlNets")
	- View net		    CALL("VisuNet")
    Second line :
	- Create the netlist	    CALL("NewCreateNets")
	- Sauve netlist on disk     CALL("Nets2File")
	- Call Spice simlator	    CALL("Simulation")
	- Plot simulation results   CALL("AmiPlot")
	- Link simulation scripts   CALL("Simulate")
	- Undo			     MENU("Undo")
	- Delete netlist from memory DELARRAY(EQUI):DELARRAY(LABEL):NETS=0
	- Delete netlist and simulation files	CALL("PurgeTempFiles")
	- free
@ENDNODE
@NODE EditionBar "AmiCAD Edition toolbar"
@TOC ToolBars

    This toolbar have 6 columns by 3 lines of icons.
    First line (from left to right) :
	- Move to left		    IF(FIRSTSEL,IF(SNAPGRID(2),P__=SETGRID(0),P__=1):SAVEALL:MOVE(0,-P__,0),MESSAGE("Aucune sélection en cours"))
	- Move to top		    IF(FIRSTSEL,IF(SNAPGRID(2),P__=SETGRID(0),P__=1):SAVEALL:MOVE(0,0,-P__),MESSAGE("Aucune sélection en cours"))
	- Draw cartouche	    CALL("Cartouche","Amiga")
	- Cut			    MENU("Cut")
	- Use clip 1		    CURSMODE(-1):CLIPUNIT(1)
		Initialization	    CLIPUNIT(0)==1
	- Create the netlist	    CALL("NewCreateNets")
    Seconde ligne :
	- Move to bottom	    IF(FIRSTSEL,IF(SNAPGRID(2),P__=SETGRID(0),P__=1):SAVEALL:MOVE(0,0,P__),MESSAGE("Aucune sélection en cours"))
	- Move to right 	    IF(FIRSTSEL,IF(SNAPGRID(2),P__=SETGRID(0),P__=1):SAVEALL:MOVE(0,P__,0),MESSAGE("Aucune sélection en cours"))
	- Reduce window size	    CALL("Redimensionner")
	- Copy			    MENU("Copy")
	- Use clip 2		    CURSMODE(-1):CLIPUNIT(2)
		Initialization	    CLIPUNIT(0)==2
	- Save AmiPCB netlist	    CALL("CAD2PCB")
    Troisičme ligne :
	- Delete objects	    MENU("Delete")
	- Undo			    MENU("Undo")
	- Edit objects		    EDITMUL(0,0)
	- Paste 		    CURSMODE(-1):MENU("Paste")
	- Use clip 3		    CURSMODE(-1):CLIPUNIT(3)
		Initialization	    CLIPUNIT(0)==3
	- Call AmiPCB		    CALL("AmiPCB")
@ENDNODE
@NODE DrawingBar "AmiCAD Drawing toolbar"
@TOC ToolBars

    This toolbar have 7 columns by 6 lines of icons.
    First line (from left to right) :
	- Place wires		    UNMARK(-1):MENU("Place text")
		Initialisation	    (CURSMODE(-1)==2)&(DRAWMODE(1000)==1)
	- Small grid		    SETGRID(5)
