@ENDNODE
@NODE AmiPlot "AmiPlot"

    This program has been written to display the results of a simulation
    done with Spice. It reads the rawfile, saved in the RAM: disk.
    Naturelly, you must have called the @{"Simulation" LINK Simulation.AmiCAD}) script before
    calling AmiPlot.
    Many features are not implemented for the moment : zoom, scroll,
    printing, mouse are not supported.
    You can use a GUI (called using the menu) to modify some values
    like the x and y limits, labels...

    The Shell template of the program is :
	FILE/K,S=SIGNAL/M,REQ/S,SCREEN/K,LEFT/N,TOP/N,W=WIDTH/N,H=HEIGHT/N,
	POLAR/S,NOGRID/S,LINEAR/S,LOGLOG/S,XLOG/S,YLOG/S,XDELTA/K,YDELTA/K,
	XVAR/K,XMIN/K,XMAX/K,YMIN/K,YMAX/K,INDICEMIN/N,INDICEMAX/N,XLABEL/K,
	YLABEL/K,XUNITS/K,YUNITS/K,XCOMPRESS/N,LINPLOT/S,COMBPLOT/S,
	POINTPLOT/S,TITLE/K

    The main arguments are :
	FILE : name of the rawfile to read. If no file is given the GUI is
	opened.
	SIGNAL : names of the signals to display. If it's not present all
	available signals will be ploted. You can include several SIGNAL
	in the same command if needed. The GUI can then modify the state of
	each signal.
	REQ : will open the GUI.
	SCREEN : defines the name of the screen where the plot will be
	drawned. Can be usefull if AmiCAD is running on its own screen.
	LEFT, TOP, WIDTH, HEIGHT : define the position and the dimensions
	of the plot window.

    Examples :
	AmiPlot FILE RAM:test_data
	AmiPlot FILE RAM:test_data SCREEN AmiCAD
	AmiPlot FILE RAM:test_data SIGNAL V(VE)
	AmiPlot FILE RAM:test_data SIGNAL V(VE) V(VOUT)
	AmiPlot FILE RAM:test_data SIGNAL V(VE) SIGNAL V(VOUT)
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Fonctions" "List of ARexx functions"
@TOC "Macros"

  @{"ABS     " LINK ABS} computes the absolute value of a number
  @{"ARC     " LINK ARC} places an arc
  @{"ARRAYDIM" LINK ARRAYDIM} read an element of an array
  @{"ASC     " LINK ASC} returns an ASCII code
  @{"BLINK   " LINK BLINK} draws and clears an object
  @{"BOX     " LINK BOX} draws a rectangle
  @{"CADPATH " LINK CADPATH} returns the program path
  @{"CALL    " LINK CALL} calls an ARexx script
  @{"CHR     " LINK CHR} returns the character having the ASCII code specified
  @{"CLIPPATH" LINK CLIPPATH} specify the drawer containing clips
  @{"CLIPUNIT" LINK CLIPUNIT} specify the memory area used for the operations CUT, COPY, PASTE
  @{"CLOSE   " LINK CLOSE} close the window
  @{"CLOSEBAR" LINK CLOSEBAR}  close a toolbar
  @{"COL     " LINK COL} number of the column where an object is located
  @{"CONVERT " LINK CONVERT} display alternate symbol for component
  @{"COORDS  " LINK COORDS} returns the co-ordinates of an object
  @{"COPY    " LINK COPY} copy one or more objects into memory
  @{"CURSMODE" LINK CURSMODE} chose an object placement mode
  @{"DATE    " LINK DATE} returns the actual date
  @{"DEF     " LINK DEF} defines a new function
  @{"DELARRAY" LINK DELARRAY} removes an array from memory
  @{"DELETE  " LINK DELETE} removal of an object
  @{"DEVPINS " LINK DEVPINS} returns the number of connexions of a component
  @{"DIMARRAY" LINK DIMARRAY} set an array
  @{"DIMSHEET" LINK DIMSHEET} dimensions the window (SuperBitmap)
  @{"DRAW    " LINK DRAW} trace a line
  @{"DRAWMODE" LINK DRAWMODE} selection of the type of layout
  @{"EDIT    " LINK EDIT} call the edit requester
  @{"EDITBAR " LINK EDITBAR} edit a toolbar
  @{"EDITMUL " LINK EDITMUL} edit several objects
  @{"ELLIPSE " LINK ELLIPSE} traces an ellipse or a circle
  @{"ENDCOL  " LINK ENDCOL} returns the abciss of an end of line
  @{"ENDLINE " LINK ENDLINE} returns the number of the line of an end of line
  @{"EXEC    " LINK EXEC} interpret a string of characters
  @{"FILENAME" LINK FILENAME} name of complete file, (including path)
  @{"FILEPART" LINK FILEPART} name of file
  @{"FINDLAB " LINK FINDLAB} look for a label
  @{"FINDLINE" LINK FINDLINE} look for a line
  @{"FINDOBJ " LINK FINDOBJ} look for an object
  @{"FINDPART" LINK FINDPART} look for a component
  @{"FINDREF " LINK FINDREF} search for a component by its reference
  @{"FINDVAL " LINK FINDVAL} search for a component by its value
